{Just to prove that this result was no fluke, I then had the chance to play
world championship finalist, Boris Gelfand. Yet again the opening worked a
treat and this time, I know that my opponent had prepared. --- The following
game must rate as one of my best-ever victories, but to be honest it was a
very scrappy game, with some rather poor play from both sides at certain
points. The game became very messy and somehow, I managed to find my way
through the murkiness. In general, I enjoy playing games that have entered
'the chaos zone', as trench fighting is one of my strong points. --- The
opening itself worked very well for me, and that must give some indication of
just how dangerous the Classical Dutch can be, even to some of the best
players in the world. --- If you want to enter this weird world, please read
on...} 1. d4 e6 2. c4 f5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O d6 7. b4 ({
Avoiding the main line after} 7. Nc3 Ne4 8. Nxe4 fxe4 {. Maybe this is an
indication that my opponent also thought that the Dutch with 7...Ne4 is fine
for Black!? Two rounds later, I faced the super-strong, Hikaru Nakamura with
Black. That game started 1 d4 e6 2 e4!?, so yet again, is that a sign that
Nakamura could not find any way to gain an advantage against the Classical
Dutch!?}) 7... a5 {I played this move in order to avoid White holding his
pawns together with a3.} (7... Ne4 8. Bb2 a5 9. a3 (9. b5 a4 $1) 9... axb4 10.
axb4 Rxa1 11. Bxa1 d5 {may be fine for Black though.}) 8. b5 Ne4 9. Qc2 Bf6 10.
Bb2 a4 11. Nfd2 d5 {It makes sense to transpose to a Stonewall structure, when
White has played an early b4.} 12. Na3 c6 13. Rab1 Bd7 14. Rfc1 {I am not
totally convinced by this move, as the rook does not seem to be doing a great
deal on c1.} ({It would have made more sense to have continued with the move} 
14. e3 $1 {when White puts a permanent stop to my plans of playing ...f4. This
move also makes it difficult for me to make progress on the kingside. I can
try playing ...g5 but then White can always respond with f4, keeping the
position closed over there. Even so, having said all of the above, my position
does seem fine if I now undertake some active operations on the queenside. For
example:} cxb5 15. Nxb5 Bxb5 16. cxb5 Nd7 {with a perfectly fine position for
Black.}) 14... Be8 15. Nf3 $2 {This is a serious mistake that allows me to
gain a very dangerous initiative on the kingside.} f4 $1 {This move will often
blow things wide open on the kingside. I now have ideas of playing ...Bg6
followed by capturing on g3. In all of the following lines White is very weak
on the f2-square. Black must be doing very well now and I have to say that at
the time, I was wondering what I had missed!} 16. Qd1 ({Weaker is} 16. gxf4 {
, due to} Bg6 17. Qd1 Bh4 {, when all my pieces come flooding into White's
position.}) 16... fxg3 17. hxg3 Bg6 ({Another option was} 17... Bg5 {, but
this allows White to defend his weak e3-square after} 18. Nxg5 Qxg5 19. Bxe4
dxe4 20. Rc3 {.}) 18. bxc6 Nxc6 19. Nb5 Bg5 20. Ba3 Rf7 ({Another tempting
option was} 20... Bxc1 {, which should also be much better for Black, for
example,} 21. Bxf8 Be3 22. fxe3 Qxf8 {and White has a number of problems to
solve on the kingside. I avoided this line, because I noticed a very
interesting rook sacrifice, which looked very strong...}) 21. Nxg5 Qxg5 22.
Bxe4 dxe4 {White's kingside is in serious danger of collapsing.} ({This is
superior to} 22... Bxe4 {as that would allow} 23. Nd6 {.}) 23. Qe1 ({I was
expecting} 23. Nd6 {, when I was planning to sacrifice my rook:} Rxf2 $1 24.
Kxf2 Rf8+ 25. Kg2 (25. Ke1 e3) 25... e3 26. Qg1 Bxb1 (26... Rf2+ 27. Qxf2 exf2
28. Rxb7 h5 29. Kxf2 h4) 27. Rf1 Bf5 28. Nxf5 Rxf5 {with a big attack, and I
don't think White can defend.}) 23... e3 24. f3 Bxb1 25. Rxb1 Rf6 26. Kg2 Rh6
27. g4 Ne7 $2 {Making life very difficult for myself!} ({I could have won
immediately by playing} 27... Nxd4 28. Nxd4 Qf4 29. Qg3 Qxd4 {.}) 28. Bxe7 Qxe7
29. Qg3 Rd8 30. Qe5 Qh4 31. Qg3 {We have reached a very tense position and I
realised at this point that I had let things slip. A draw is still on the
cards but, in life, a player like me is not often given a chance to beat the
world championship finalist with my favourite opening. Chances like that must
be taken and, for better or worse, I have always been a gambler.} Qe7 32. Qe5
Rg6 $5 33. c5 Rg5 34. Qxe3 h5 35. Nd6 hxg4 36. f4 Rh5 37. Qg3 $2 {After
rolling the dice my opponent is the first to go wrong. We were both in serious
time trouble, so this is understandable. White should be losing after this
error.} ({Gelfand should have tried} 37. Rxb7 {, when I was planning to keep
the game alive with} Qf6 {, but who knows what the correct assessment of this
position is!} (37... Qh4 {looked like a draw after} 38. Qxe6+ Kh8 39. Nf7+ Kh7
40. Ng5+ Rxg5 41. fxg5 Qh3+ 42. Kg1 Rf8 43. Qh6+ $3 {.})) 37... Qf6 38. Qxg4
Rh6 39. f5 {White's king is left too weak after this move,} ({but his position
was very tricky anyway, for example,} 39. Kf3 {allows my queen to enter the
position after} Qxd4 {.}) 39... exf5 40. Nxf5 Rg6 41. Ne7+ Qxe7 42. Qxg6 Qxe2+
43. Kh3 Rd5 ({Gelfand resigned here, due to something like the following line...} 43... Rd5 44. Rg1 Qf3+ 45. Kh4 Rxd4+ 46. Rg4 Rxg4+ 47. Qxg4 Qxg4+ 48. Kxg4
Kf7 {.}) (43... -- {At this point I turned into a shaking mess, as all the
adrenaline started to flow out of body, but I have to admit it was one of the
best feelings that I have ever had playing chess. That is why we all love the
