{The following game is a great advertisement for the Classical Dutch. Richard
Pert, a good friend of mine, played this game fantastically, as he
demonstrated just how dangerous the attack can become. The game also shows
some important points that are worth bearing in mind. Let's take a look.} 1.
Nf3 f5 {From the start, Black takes control of the central e4-square.} 2. g3 (
2. d3 {is quite an annoying response to 1...f5, as now an early e4 can open up
Black's position. We will examine this response in detail in Section 7.}) 2...
Nf6 3. Bg2 d6 ({This aims to save a tempo i.e.} 3... e6 4. O-O Be7 5. d3 d6 6.
c4 e5 {and Black has moved his e-pawn twice.}) 4. O-O ({White can also play} 4.
d4 {which stops ...e5. Black then has the option of staying with the Classical
Dutch with ...e6 or switching to a Leningrad with ...g6.}) 4... e5 {The goal
of any Classical Dutch player is to achieve this push. Once Black has played ..
.e5 it gives him a strong centre and a chance to attack on the kingside.} 5. d3
$6 {I already think that this move is a slight mistake. White is playing the
opening without too much thought. After this move, Black's plan of action
pretty much plays itself. --- This just goes to show that some players
automatically play their opening moves against any set-up. Chess is a
complicated game and you need to think from an early stage. This is especially
true if your opponent plays something unexpected in the opening!} (5. d4 {is a
better move, as at least this disrupts Black's set-up.}) 5... Be7 6. c4 O-O 7.
Nc3 a5 {Black can also play without this move, as I sometimes feel that the
exchange of a-pawns can actually help White. This is due to the fact that
White will generally be attacking on the queenside whilst Black will be
attacking on the kingside, and after a3-b4 and the exchange ...axb4 axb4,
White has the open a-file to play down.} 8. Rb1 {Preparing to launch with a3
and b4.} (8. a3 Kh8 9. Rb1 Qe8 10. b4 axb4 11. axb4 {transposes.}) 8... Kh8 {
Black does not need to play this move straightaway but it is useful to move
the king away from the a2-g8 diagonal. At some point in the future, White will
often move his queen to b3 and at least Black can now avoid any nasty checks.}
9. a3 {Let's take a time-out. --- I was watching this game and had noticed
that both sides had reached this position using hardly any time on their
clocks. It was only around now that they started to knuckle down. White is
planning b4, b5/c5 and then hopefully, he will be able to create a weakness on
the queenside. Black, on the other hand, is not going to mess about. He is not
interested in creating a weakness. Black just wants to checkmate White's king!
--- To do this, Black will need to play: ...Qe8, Qh5, f4, Bh3, Ng4, fxg3, Bxg2,
Rxf3, and Qxh2#! --- You will be amazed at how many times this plan is
successful. Anyway, to sum up the position, I would always say that it is more
fun to attack your opponent's king than anything else. White may win a pawn on
the queenside if his attack is successful. On the other hand, if Black's
attack successful, he will checkmate White!} Qe8 $1 {BRAINSTORMING POINT! ---
This is Step 1 of Black's plan... --- If you are going to reach the 'Jedi
Knight level' then you must become familiar with this plan! --- ...Qe8 and ...Qh5 is an important idea. The queen is often well placed on h5. --- ...Qh5
won't checkmate White on its own but when combined with ...e5 ...f4 ...Bh3 and
...Ng4, Black's attack can be very dangerous. --- Just look at what happens in
this game...} 10. b4 Qh5 {BRAINSTORMING POINT! --- Step 2...The queen finds
its ideal square --- The main piece that is defending White's kingside is his
light-squared bishop. --- If Black can swap off White's light-squared bishop
then the light squares around White's king will become especially weak. ---
For that reason, Black plans on playing ...Bh3 at some point.} 11. Qb3 $2 {
White is playing without a care in the world. This move does not do anything;
it may actually make White's position worse. Having the queen on d1 gives
White more chances to defend.} ({White should have played} 11. e3 $1 {. At
least this attempts to stop ...f4. White would also love to swap the queens
and now this may be possible if he can move the knight on f3.}) 11... f4 {
Simple.} 12. Nd5 {White hopes that the exchange of knights will ease his
defence, but Black has another knight!} Nxd5 13. cxd5 {The open c-file is not
a major concern for Black as he can always defend c7 with the move Bd8. The
main factor is White's king!} axb4 14. axb4 {What would you play here? ---
Black has a promising position but what piece is not taking part in the game?}
Nd7 $1 {Correct! This knight has a good future and Black will eventually
manoeuvre it to f6 and then to g4 where it can participate in the attack.} 15.
Bd2 Nf6 $1 {Black is sending all of his pieces the right way.} 16. Ra1 {
White's counterplay on the queenside is far too slow.} Rb8 17. Rfc1 Bh3 $5 {
This is slightly risky as it does sacrifice a pawn, but if White captures on
c7 then Black will be able to activate his dark-squared bishop - the only
minor piece that is currently not doing a lot.} (17... Bd8 {is a perfectly
safe option.}) 18. Be1 {This is rather passive.} ({White should probably have
tried} 18. Rxc7 {. White is defending desperately anyway, so it may have been
best to capture this pawn. At least this way, White has a material advantage.
If Black does not checkmate White then this could count in the long run. ---
Play could continue} Bd8 19. Rcc1 Bb6 {, which still looks very good for Black.
I would be surprised if the white king can last for another ten moves.}) 18...
Ng4 {Black's opening plan has worked a treat.} 19. b5 ({Again, I think White
should have tried} 19. Rxc7 Bd8 20. Rc4 {with some defensive chances:} Bb6 21.
Ra2 {.}) 19... fxg3 {Opening up the f-file. At the moment, White's knight
defends the pawn on h2, so Black aims to capture this knight in order to take
the defence away from h2.} 20. hxg3 {The only option,} ({as} 20. fxg3 {loses to
} Bxg2 21. Kxg2 Rxf3 $1 {(a standard plan in this type of position, which rips
White's kingside apart)} 22. exf3 (22. Kxf3 Rf8+ 23. Ke4 (23. Kg2 Qxh2#) 23...
Qg6#) 22... Qxh2+ 23. Kf1 Ne3# {.}) 20... Rf6 {Now that White has played hxg3,
the h-file is exposed. For this reason, Black brings his rook to h6.} (20...
Bxg2 {was also very strong, for example,} 21. Kxg2 {and now} Rf6 (21... Rxf3 $2
{would be a mistake as White's king can escape:} 22. exf3 Qh2+ 23. Kf1 Qh1+ 24.
Ke2 {and White is over the worst.})) 21. Qa4 $2 {It is all over now.} ({A
better try was} 21. Bh1 {but} Bf1 $1 {should be mating.}) 21... Bxg2 22. Kxg2
Rh6 23. Ng1 {It is mate in two now. I will give you a couple of seconds to
solve it...} Qh1+ 24. Kf1 Nh2# {. A nice game. Black made things look so
simple. This is the kind of game that makes chess look easy!} 0-1

