{In this game we see Magnus entering into a Dutch set-up via a rather
irregular move order. This idea of transposing from positions independent of
the opening will be looked at later on in the Introduction to this book.} 1. c4
e5 {Of course, this is not our main recommendation in this book, but as we
will see Magnus gains a great 'Dutch-like' position.} 2. Nc3 (2. g3 f5 $6 {I
have always been slightly dubious about this move because of White's reply;} (
2... Nc6 $1 {is a much better move order, when Black intends to play ...f5
whilst stopping White from breaking in the centre with d4}) 3. d4 $1 {(Now
Black cannot adequately keep his pawns on e5 and f5)} e4 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Bg2 c6
6. d5 Bb4 7. Bd2 Na6 8. Nh3 O-O 9. O-O cxd5 10. Nxd5 Nxd5 11. cxd5 Bxd2 12.
Qxd2 {and White had a very pleasant advantage in P.Svidler-M.Carlsen, Astana
