1. d4 f5 {. I will quickly talk about the structure of this book and some
important things to bear in mind when working your way through it. --- In the
past, when I have been learning a new opening, I have always found that the
best way to do this is to understand the reasoning behind the moves played and
not the actual moves themselves. It is much more important to understand the
concept behind an idea rather than to memorise a series of moves without any
real understanding as to why those moves should be played. --- To enforce this
point, I have used a number of methods throughout this book which will help
the reader increase their understanding of the Classical Dutch. --- Firstly, I
have used several 'brainstorming points' in order to explain the reasoning
behind the moves played and what each side is trying to achieve in the given
position. --- Furthermore, a lot of the key points are repeated throughout
this book, again with the intention of making the idea more memorable. This
has been done systematically in order to help the reader commit the same ideas
to memory and become 'a Jedi Knight of the Classical Dutch'! --- Finally, at
the end of some of the chapters, I have used a series of tests to assess
whether the main concepts of the chapter have been fully understood. If you
have read the chapter then these tests should not pose too much of a problem
but then again, they are there to reinforce the main ideas behind the
Classical Dutch. --- I can honestly say that there are not too many 'Jedi
Knight' level, Classical Dutch players in existence. Can you obtain that rank?}
