{Let's now take a look at another idea that is very important in the Classical
Dutch. --- BRAINSTORMING POINT! --- You should always aim to meet the pawn
push d4-d5 with the counter push ...e5. --- This idea is better explained with
the use of an example. First of all we will look at an example where Black
plays incorrectly and gets himself into a position where he cannot meet the
push d5 with the push ...e5.} 1. d4 f5 2. g3 e6 3. Bg2 Nf6 4. Nf3 Be7 5. O-O
O-O 6. c4 Nc6 $6 {Black has to be careful about placing his knight here. In
general, the following rule is worth remembering. --- Rule 6: Meet d5 with ...e5: As you can see, the above-mentioned rule is not possible here and White
should play:} 7. d5 $1 {. Giving White an advantage. This is one reason why
it is often worth delaying the development of the knight on c6. As we have
mentioned before, often Black should also delay the development of his
queenside bishop on c8 as well. In other words, leave your queenside pieces
alone!} *

