{Rule 8: The Pawn breaks ...h5-h4 and ...a5-a4 --- BRAINSTORMING POINT! --- In
the middlegame, if the pawn structure has become closed and White has played
g3 and Bg2, Black can often start an attack against the enemy king with ...h5,
...h4, ...hxg3! --- Example 1: ...h5-h4: This is a typical middlegame position,
and the type of position that Black should be aiming for when playing the
Classical Dutch. Black's main advantage is his strong central pawns on e5 and
f5. Clearly Black played the advance ...e5 earlier and it worked well to lead
to this position. --- But what to do now? --- I now played a strong plan.} 
15... e4 $1 {Gaining space and making White's bishop on g2 a bad piece.} 16.
Ne1 h5 $1 {With the aim of softening up White's kingside with ...h4 and ...hxg3. This is a plan worth remembering as it can occur often in the Dutch,
even in the endgame!} 17. f3 $1 h4 18. fxe4 hxg3 19. hxg3 Qc5+ 20. Kh2 Bxb2 21.
Nd3 Qe3 22. Qxb2 Rf6 23. Nf4 $2 Rh6+ $1 {My plan has been a success: White's
king has become exposed to attack. --- BRAINSTORMING POINT! --- The plan ...h5,
...h4 and ...hxg3 works a lot better when the position is closed. This is
because the plan takes time, and there may be more important issues to deal
with first. --- Let's see a couple more moves.} 24. Nh3 fxe4 25. Qd2 Qxd2 26.
Rxd2 a4 $1 {BRAINSTORMING POINT! --- ...a4 is often a great way to 'soften up'
your opponent's queenside pawn formation of a2 (a3), b3, c4. In the same way
as ...h5-h4, White's pawns become a target after this plan.} 27. b4 Be6 {With
a winning position for Black.} *

