{Example 3: ...h5-h4: We see the same plan in action below, albeit it in a
rather strange way. I was playing with the white pieces, and just to make
things even more confusing, I was paired against my namesake S.Williams! --- A
number of strange things have occurred to me and other S.Williams' throughout
my life as a chess professional. Around about ten years previous to this game,
FIDE had used "the other" S.Williams games to rate my performance on the new
FIDE rating list. So there I was, on my way to my first game at the Hastings
international, expecting my rating to be about 2450, when I got a major shock
to see that my rating had dropped to 2250! Thanks FIDE! --- On another
occasion I had done some coaching work for two solid weeks for the English
junior team. My payment cheque for this work got sent out to another S.Williams, who lived about 200 miles from me! Luckily he was very honest and
passed the payment onto me! Thanks English Chess Federation! --- The game
below started off as a Classical Dutch reversed (as in Svidler-Carlsen and
Williams-Zhong Zhao). I will show you the opening moves, just out of interest.
--- It is worth noting that what you can learn in the Classical Dutch can
clearly be transferred to other openings and vice versa. Transferable skills
are always a good thing to have, and we will take a more detailed look at this
later.} 1. e4 c5 2. Be2 e6 3. f4 d5 4. d3 g6 5. Nf3 Bg7 6. O-O Ne7 7. Qe1 b5 8.
Nc3 b4 9. Nd1 Bb7 10. Nf2 Nbc6 11. a3 a5 12. Rb1 Qb6 13. Be3 Rc8 14. c3 O-O 15.
Kh1 Ba6 {The position is fairly even, as Black can often stop an attack based
on Ng4 and Qh4 with ...f5! For that reason I need to think of another plan. So
I played the standard:} 16. h4 $1 {This aims to soften up Black's kingside in
the typical fashion that we have seen already.} Rc7 17. h5 d4 $2 {The wrong
plan. Black should capture the pawn on h5 with ...gxh5 when the position
remains equal. This is a move that Black missed a couple of times.} 18. Bd2
dxc3 19. bxc3 Rb7 $2 {Too slow. As on move 17, Black had to capture the h-pawn
with ...gxh5. Now I gain a winning attack, very quickly.} 20. hxg6 hxg6 21. Ng4
$1 {My pieces now come flooding into the attack. My simple plan of removing
the h-pawns from the board has left Black's king mortally weak. The game
finished.} Rfb8 22. Qh4 Qd8 23. Ng5 bxc3 24. Nf6+ Kf8 25. Ngh7# {. A pretty
end to the game, very sporting of my opponent. (Players called S.Williams are
often good, sporting players...)} 1-0

