{What openings are similar to the Dutch? --- Can you use this to your
advantage? --- The Classical Dutch has a lot of similarities with various
other openings. These similarities might come in the type of pawn structure,
typical middlegame plans and various other forms. You can aim to use to this
to your advantage by keeping things simple and picking openings that follow
the same trends. --- What openings do I consider to be similar to the
Classical Dutch? The list below are openings that keep the same
characteristics:} 1. -- {White perspective:} ({Bird's Opening:} 1. f4 {Plus
Points: This is the Dutch reversed with an extra tempo! We saw me use this
opening in one the introductory games to score a good victory. If you want to
save a lot of time learning how to play with the white pieces, then this could
be an interesting way to play. --- I have used this move from time to time,
and I basically aim to do precisely what I would do in the normal Classical
Dutch, but a tempo up. --- I am normally careful who I play this plan against.
I would normally only play 1 f4 against players who always play 1 e4
themselves. --- Why? --- I want to get people out of what they are used to
playing, and by playing 1 f4 the position will transpose into a 1 d4 opening
reversed, and if my opponent always plays 1 e4 he will be uncomfortable with
the position that he has been forced into. --- All in all, 1 f4 for me is a
great surprise weapon. --- Downside: The only extra thing that you need to
learn here is From's Gambit, which is where Black plays 1...e5! Then you have
the option of capturing the pawn or entering into a Kings Gambit with the move
2 e4!?. --- Nowadays I use 1 f4 as a surprise opening, as it gets a bit boring
playing the Dutch all the time. It is a good idea to try to understand new
positions, as this will increase your overall understanding of our great game.
--- You should also be trying to gain an opening advantage when playing with
the white pieces, and as good as the Classical Dutch is, it does not offer any
advantage to Black (or White in this case!).}) ({The Grand Prix:} 1. e4 c5 2.
Nc3 {With the idea of playing f4! next.} ({or} 2. f4) 2... d6 3. f4 {If you
are a 1 e4 player, then I would suggest that learning the Grand Prix against
the Sicilian is a very good idea. --- Both openings have a lot of similar
themes and if you know what to do in the Classical Dutch after playing ...e5,
then you will know how to attack in the Grand Prix. --- Take a look at the
following game which came from one of my games with the White pieces.}) *

