1. d4 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. Nf3 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6 7. Nc3 a5 8. Re1 {
This used to be the old main line and 8 Re1 was the move I feared! --- Black
certainly needs to know what he is doing against this move. White is planning
to play e4 when he will gain a positional advantage. Black should aim to stop
this at all costs. --- BRAINSTORMING POINT! --- At the start of this book, I
pointed out some basic strategic points that Black needs to know. One of these
springs to mind now. --- If White can achieve the e4 advance without Black
playing ...e5 and Black has to exchange with ...fxe4, White will generally
obtain an advantage. --- Black has to stop White from playing e4 here. There
is only one way of doing this.} Ne4 {This move is pretty much forced. ---
BRAINSTORMING POINT! --- Black must stop White from playing e4!} 9. Qc2 Nxc3 $1
{This is an important improvement on the old main line (see later).} 10. Qxc3 {
This is the natural response to 9...Nxc3! as it keeps White's pawns intact but
I don't believe that it is the best move.} ({We will take a look at} 10. bxc3
$1 {in the Theory section of this book, as this move is a better attempt at
gaining an opening advantage for White.}) 10... Nc6 $1 {I now had a long think
as I had to try and do something about White's plan of playing e4. The real
point of ...Nc6 becomes clear after White's next move.} 11. e4 {BRAINSTORMING
POINT! --- Let's go back to one of the general rules. You should know it by
now: If White can achieve the e4 advance without Black playing ...e5 and Black
has to exchange with ...fxe4, White will generally obtain an advantage.} e5 $1
{Yes, this is the correct response! We can now see why the pawn on a5 is good.
It secures the b4-square for a black piece. This dynamic move holds the
position together. Only the central counter-strike will stop White from
gaining an advantage.} 12. exf5 {We will come back to White's two other
possibilities in the theory section.} Bxf5 13. Be3 $2 {This is too passive.} ({
White should have tried} 13. dxe5 {which is looked at below.}) 13... Be4 {An
exchange of light-squared bishops can only help Black. White will then have
some weakened squares around his kingside (h3, g2, f3) and will have lost his
best minor piece, the light-squared bishop. Furthermore, White's light-squared
bishop often puts pressure on Black's queenside.} 14. Nd2 $6 (14. Bd2 {was
better.}) 14... Bxg2 15. Kxg2 d5 $1 {It is time to pause and reflect on the
position that has arisen from the opening. White's pieces are all looking
rather passive, whilst Black's position is starting to come alive. With the
last move 15...d5! Black starts to attack White's centre, which could crumble
at any moment.} 16. a3 Bf6 17. Nf3 exd4 18. Nxd4 Qd7 19. Rad1 Ne5 20. c5 Nf3 $1
{A tricky move for White to deal with.} 21. Rf1 Qg4 $6 {This was tempting but
not the best move.} ({I should have played} 21... Ra6 $1 {with the idea of
getting Black's last piece over to the kingside. This is another reason why 7...a5!? was a good move! Black is planning ...Bxd4 and ...Rh6, for example,} 22.
h3 Bxd4 23. Bxd4 Rh6 {and Black is winning.}) 22. Qd3 Bxd4 23. Bxd4 Nh4+ 24.
Kh1 Nf3 25. Kg2 c6 26. h3 Qe6 27. Be3 g5 28. Bd4 $6 ({White should have played
} 28. Bf4 $1 {when he is over the worst, although Black may still be slightly
better, for example,} Nh4+ 29. gxh4 gxf4 {.}) 28... Rae8 {White has a few
problems now as he has no way of improving his position.} 29. b4 axb4 30. axb4
Qd7 31. Ba1 Qe6 32. Rc1 d4 33. Rfd1 Rf7 34. Qc4 Qe4 35. Kf1 Nd2+ 0-1

