{Let's take a look at another game that I have played in this variation. This
time, we will concentrate on 8 b3, which is one of White's most popular moves.
} 1. d4 e6 2. c4 f5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O d6 7. Nc3 a5 $5 {
This game was played at the Cappelle la Grande tournament in France. My
opponent was a Russian GM. I have to admit that I was very annoyed with myself
after the game, because I felt that I had achieved a good position from the
opening. I then went on to throw it away. Never a pleasant feeling in chess!}
8. b3 {White will often choose this positional move which I now consider to be
the main line. The plan is to simply play Bb2 gaining extra control over e5.}
Ne4 {This is a common plan in this type of structure. As Black's position is
more cramped, exchanges tend to help him. It is also now possible for Black to
move his bishop to f6.} 9. Bb2 Nxc3 $5 {I believe that this is Black's best
chance. The general plan is to meet e4 with ...f4 when Black often has chances
to attack on the kingside.} ({I used to play} 9... Bf6 {on a regular basis but
I had some difficulty finding a good response to} 10. Qc2 Nxc3 11. Bxc3 {, for
example} Nc6 12. e4 $1 fxe4 13. Qxe4 {. --- BRAINSTORMING POINT! --- This type
of structure is worth avoiding at all costs! --- After} Qe8 14. Rfe1 {White
had a dream position and went on to win in R.Ruck-S.Williams, European
under-20 Championship 1997.}) 10. Bxc3 Qe8 {The black queen wriggles its way
around to h5. White has a number of options here.} 11. Re1 {A very logical
move. The rook is well placed behind the e-pawn. One logical plan is e4-e5.}
Qh5 $1 {An active square for the queen.} ({I once tried} 11... c6 $6 {in this
position, but I soon got myself into trouble:} 12. e4 f4 13. d5 $1 cxd5 14. e5
$1 {(a brilliant idea; White has sacrificed a pawn in order to stop Black from
meeting e5 with the standard ...d5 and Black is now forced to open the e-file)}
dxe5 15. cxd5 fxg3 16. hxg3 Qf7 17. Qd2 {and White was clearly better and duly
won in J.Benjamin-S.Williams, Bunratty Masters 2007.}) 12. e4 {BRAINSTORMING
POINT! --- Capturing on e4 would give White the type of position that he wants.
We have to avoid this at all costs and play a different plan. What should that
plan be?} f4 $1 {That's right! --- BRAINSTORMING POINT! --- From a positional
point of view, Black is forced to meet 12 e4 with 12...f4. If the e-file is
ever opened, Black will be positionally lost. Black must always aim to keep a
White pawn on the e-file. --- The move ...f4 gives Black good attacking
chances on the kingside. As you will see, the f-pawn will eventually become a
thorn in White's side.} (12... fxe4 $2 13. Rxe4 {Black must avoid this type of
structure! White will always have pressure against Black's pawn on e6. Black
is also left with a cramped and passive position. This was not the reason
behind choosing to play the Dutch!}) 13. e5 (13. Qd2 {was played against me in
G.Kjartansson-S.Williams, Hastings Masters 2000, with the following
possibilities:} -- ({. I played} 13... fxg3 14. fxg3 e5 $6 {, which leads to
some complications, where I am sure White has an improvement on the game:} (
14... a4 $5) 15. dxe5 $1 Rxf3 16. Qd1 Bg4 17. Bxf3 Bxf3 18. Qd5+ Kh8 19. Qxb7
Qh3 {. --- Bizarrely, the game is probably a draw now!} 20. Kf2 Qg2+ 21. Ke3
Bg5+ 22. Kd3 Be2+ 23. Rxe2 Qf3+ 24. Kc2 Qxe2+ 25. Kb1 Qf1+ 26. Kb2 Qf2+ 27. Kb1
Qg1+ 28. Kb2 Qf2+ 29. Kb1 Qf1+ 30. Kb2 Qf2+ {and we agreed a draw.}) (13... g5
$1 {was the other critical choice and would be the move that I would play in
the future.} 14. h3 $1 {White really has to prevent Black's ...g4 advance;} (
14. gxf4 $5 g4 $5 (14... Rxf4 {is safer for Black and looks fine}) 15. Ng5 h6
16. Nxe6 Bxe6 {is unclear}) 14... fxg3 15. fxg3 g4 16. hxg4 Qxg4 {. This all
looks very odd, as Black is only playing with his queen, but things are not so
clear, for example,} 17. Qf2 Nc6 18. d5 Nb4 {, with a messy type of position.})
) 13... d5 $1 {This move follows the same principle as before. Black must
avoid opening the e-file.} 14. Qd3 ({White has also tried the following
options:} 14. Nd2 {An exchange of queens can only help White, so Black is
advised to play} Qf7 15. Qf3 {. Now in Play the Classical Dutch, I recommended
the simple} c6 {which is a safe way to play. Mind you, "safe" is not really a
word in my vocabulary!} ({Instead,} 15... Nc6 $5 {is an interesting sacrifice,
when there could follow} 16. Re2 $6 ({White should really accept the sacrifice
with} 16. cxd5 exd5 17. Qxd5 Be6 18. Qf3 Rad8 {, when Black has compensation})
16... Nb4 17. a3 Nc2 {Black is playing very imaginatively. This is often what
you need to do in the Dutch!} 18. Ra2 Nxa3 19. Qd3 a4 {and Black was clearly
better in A.Knitl-D.Pirrot, Bad Wörishofen 2008.})) (14. h3 c6 (14... a4 $5 {
is often worth playing}) 15. g4 {and now in V.Erdos-R.Bellin, Budapest 2005,
Black played} Qg6 $6 {. This is the wrong square for the queen. After g4,
Black should nearly always move his queen to h6, where it keeps pressure on h3
and allows Black to play ...Bd7 ...Be8 and ...Bg6 at a later point.}) (14. Qe2
c6 15. Bd2 g5 16. h3 a4 17. Qd3 Bd7 18. g4 Qh6 19. bxa4 Rxa4 20. c5 Be8 21. a3
Nd7 22. Qb3 Ra7 23. a4 Bg6 24. Kf1 Be4 25. Ke2 Qg6 26. a5 Rfa8 27. Kd1 Bd8 28.
Ke2 $2 Bc2 {and White resigned in N.Clery-S,Williams, Cappelle La Grande 2005.}
) 14... c6 {This is a standard type of position. White has more space but
Black's pawn structure is very solid and he has chances to attack on the
kingside. Black often plays ...Bd7, ...Be8 and ...Bg6, an idea which can be
often seen in the French Defence. Another plan is ...g5-g4.} ({Another option
for Black is} 14... b6 $5 {. --- This is an interesting idea which has yet to
be played. Black wants to develop his bishop to b7, when ...dxc4 becomes a
threat. This may be the best way for Black to play in this position. I would
certainly give it a whirl. For example,} 15. h3 Bb7 16. g4 Qh6 17. Rac1 Na6 {
. Black has finished his development and he can be happy with the resulting
position, which is roughly equal.}) 15. Bd2 g5 (15... fxg3 {was possible:} 16.
fxg3 Bd7 {, but I expect that White is a bit better here as he has more space.
Black's f-pawn can often be an asset, so I preferred to avoid exchanging it.})
16. gxf4 gxf4 (16... g4 $2 {does not quite work as after} 17. Ng5 {Black
cannot play} h6 $4 {, due to} (17... Rf5 {gives White time to play} 18. h3) 18.
Qh7# {, which would be embarrassing.}) 17. Kh1 {If Black has time to bring his
two queenside pieces into the game, then he will be doing well. One thing in
Black's favour is his queen on h5 which controls a number of squares.} a4 18.
c5 Bd7 {The bishop manoeuvres around to g6.} 19. Ng1 Qh4 20. b4 Na6 {I wanted
to move this knight to b5.} 21. Ne2 {White has concentrated all his forces on
my f-pawn, but this has taken a lot of time which has given me the opportunity
to develop my pieces.} Be8 22. Rg1 Bg6 (22... Kh8 $1 {was also worth
considering. The move played in the game forces White to sacrifice the
exchange, but this gives White a pleasant initiative.}) 23. Bf3 Kh8 $6 (23...
Kf7 $5 {looks crazy but the black king is probably safer on d7, for example,}
24. Qa3 Ke8 25. Qxa4 Bd3 {with an unclear position.}) 24. Rxg6 $1 {The only
sensible plan. White's attack becomes very dangerous.} hxg6 25. Qxg6 Rg8 26.
Nxf4 $6 ({White should have played} 26. Qxe6 {when White has a big advantage.})
26... Bg5 $1 {My best chance.} 27. Qxe6 Nc7 $2 ({I should have played} 27...
Raf8 $1 28. Ng6+ Rxg6 29. Qxg6 Bxd2 {, when it is unclear how White should
continue his attack. Black is probably better.}) 28. Ng6+ Rxg6 29. Qxg6 Bxd2
30. Rg1 Qh6 31. Qf7 Rf8 $2 {The last mistake.} ({I should have tried} 31... Ne6
{which is far from clear, for example,} 32. Rg6 Qf8 33. Qxe6 Qxf3+ 34. Kg1 Rf8
{.}) 32. Qxc7 Rxf3 33. e6 {White is just winning now. The game finished:} Qf6
34. e7 Re3 35. Qd8+ Kh7 36. Qg8+ 1-0

