{'Everything in life is temporary... So if things are going well, enjoy it
because it won't last forever. And if things are going badly, don't worry. It
can't last forever either.' - Anon --- There is no point in "beating around
the bush"! I will now come directly to the reason why I have stopped playing 7.
..a5. I was considering keeping this a secret, as I still want to play this
move in the future, but I came to the conclusion that it is only fair to let
people who have purchased GingerGM and Everyman products know the truth. ---
On top of this, after originally writing this book, a game was played in the
2012 British Championship which saw the idea being used in practice.} 1. d4 f5
2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. c4 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O d6 7. Nc3 a5 8. Re1 $1 {has
always been the most critical way of meeting various variations of the
Classical Dutch and this is no exception. White is planning to play 9 e4, when
he has achieved his goal of increasing pressure on the e-file. For this reason
Black must play...} Ne4 {And now Stephen Gordon's novelty is the incredibly
strong move...} 9. Qd3 $1 {Originally, I believed that this move had no extra
benefit over 9 Qc2 but there is one major difference. White now has the
possibility to play Qd5+ in some variations which poses all sorts of problems
for Black, for example:} Nxc3 ({I will discuss Black's other interesting option
} 9... Nc6 {later on in this chapter.}) 10. bxc3 $1 {White is now ready to
play the e4 advance. Black's standard way of meeting this is to play...} Nc6 {
However, this runs into:} 11. e4 $1 {Black now has a pretty horrible decision
to make. He can either try ...e5 or capture on e4. Both moves are better for
White, for example:} -- (11... e5 {would be fine if White still had the queen
placed on c2 but in this position, White can win a pawn by playing...} 12. dxe5
dxe5 13. Qd5+ $1 {Winning Black's pawn on e5. White will play Nxe5 next which
is both simple and good!}) (11... fxe4 12. Qxe4 {might be playable for Black,
as White has doubled c-pawns, which could prove to be weak. But even so, I
strongly believe that White is just better here. He has more space and
pressure along the e-file and even the b-file. Black would prefer to have the
a-pawn back on a7, as this would allow him to arrange a plan based on ...Na5 ...b6 and ...Ba6. --- All in all, I am pessimistic about Black's chances, which
is a real shame, as I have played this variation since the age of nine! I for
one cannot find an answer to Black's problems. --- For completeness, I will
include the rest of my analysis on this variation but I would recommend that
you stick with 7...Ne4 until a solution to this line has been found.}) *

