{Most of the suggestions below have been made on my website: www.gingergm.com.
They are certainly interesting and could be well worth exploring...} 1. d4 f5
2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6 7. Nc3 a5 8. Re1 Ne4 9. Qd3
-- ({1) 'Thomas', a regular contributor on my website, has mentioned that top
Dutch expert Naumkin has used the following line:} 9... d5 $1 {I normally aim
to avoid playing ...d5 as the position then resembles a Stonewall Dutch rather
than a Classical Dutch. This can sometimes work out, as both sides have played
moves that they did not necessarily want to play. For example, Black has
played ...a5 and White has played Re1. It is very rare to see these moves
played in the Stonewall Dutch. --- Let's take a look at how the game M.Kopstov-I.Naumkin, Moscow 2002, continued:} 10. Ne5 c6 11. f3 Nxc3 12. bxc3 Nd7
13. Nxd7 Bxd7 14. e4 fxe4 15. fxe4 dxc4 16. Qxc4 b5 17. Qb3 a4 18. Qc2 e5 $1 {
