also possible to place the rook on e3, from where it gives extra protection to
White's knight on f3.} Nc6 {Black is not worried about his pawn. Instead, he
continues to develop as quickly as possible. I like Black's mentality here as
the Dutch is really an opening that requires Black to play as actively as
possible.} 13. dxe5 {The only sensible move, White should grab a pawn!} Bg4 {
Another black piece joins the attack. Black is hoping that the pin on White's
knight is worth a pawn.} 14. h3 $6 {White decides to keep things simple but
Black has no serious worries after this move.} ({White does have to be careful,
for example,} 14. exd6 Bxd6 15. h3 $6 (15. c5 {is better}) 15... Bxf3 16. Bxf3
Bxg3 $1 {(seemingly, out of nowhere, Black has a big attack!)} 17. fxg3 Qxg3+
18. Bg2 Rad8 {and all of Black's pieces are attacking.}) 14... Bxf3 15. Bxf3
dxe5 {Black should be fine now. At least he has won his pawn back!} 16. Be4 Qf6
{Black has good chances to attack on the dark squares. One of the biggest
targets is f2.} 17. Be3 {Guarding the weak f2-square.} Rad8 18. Qc2 ({A more
active move was} 18. Qh5 {, which forces Black to make a concession on the
kingside:} g6 19. Qh6 {, but after} Nd4 $1 {I quite like Black's position.})
18... h6 {This move weakens Black on the light squares, especially g6 and h7,
but there is no way that White can really attack Black on these squares. If
White could swap his queen and bishop around then he would have a good attack!}
(18... g6 19. Rad1 {may be a bit better for White.}) 19. Rad1 {White should
have an advantage now but the Dutch is a resourceful opening and Black soon
starts to make progress!} Rxd1 (19... Nd4 {is not good enough, as White can
take control of some important light squares, for example,} 20. Bxd4 Rxd4 21.
