Franklin D. Roosevelt} 1. d4 e6 2. c4 f5 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O
d6 7. Nc3 Ne4 $5 {. This is a logical move. White has a space advantage so
Black aims to alleviate his position by exchanging pieces with the move ...Ne4.
This move also frees the f6-square for Black's dark-squared bishop. I used to
think that this was the solution to all of Black's problems. That was until
White started to play 8 Nxe4! --- The latter is the only way that White can
aim to gain an advantage, but there is still not enough evidence to suggest
that the resulting position is equal or even slightly better for White. I
personally think that White has a very small advantage, but the position
remains unbalanced and is therefore extremely interesting. --- 7...Ne4 is an
easy line to remember and Black's future plans are relatively straightforward
compared with Black's other options on move eight. --- There is quite an
amusing story behind the first time that I ever played this line. I was at the
Reykjavik Open relaxing with some friends. If I recall correctly, I was in the
company of Ben Johnson (not the runner!), John Bick, Ylon Schwartz and Luis
Galego, a GM from Portugal. It was rather late at night, or more likely,
sometime in the early hours of the morning and I had just found out that I was
due to play Sokolov the following day with the black pieces. For those of you
who don't know, Ivan Sokolov is an extremely strong player with a rating of
around 2700. --- I had a deal with Ylon Schwartz that if I managed to beat
Sokolov with Black in the Classical Dutch then Ylon would have to play this
opening for the remainder of the tournament. At the time, we may have had a
couple of 'Viking' beers so it seemed like a good plan. --- The next day, I
played one of the best games in my life and I somehow managed to win
spectacularly. Ylon also won his game with the Dutch so the opening did quite
well! --- Imagine my surprise when the next time I came across Mr Schwartz was
when I turned on the television to watch the 2008 World Series of Poker. To my
shock, there was Ylon on the final table! How did this happen? At this stage
of the tournament, he was guaranteed at least two million dollars and I think
that he went on to finish in fourth place. A fantastic result and I am really
happy for him as he is a great guy and a fan of the Classical Dutch!} 8. -- *

