{After my game against Sokolov, I couldn't wait to give the 7...Ne4 variation
another go, as I was feeling very confident about the opening. The perfect
opportunity then arose in the British League, where I found myself paired
against Shirov! He is actually one of my all-time favourite players due to his
style, which is both dynamic and exciting. When he played d4 on move one, my
hopes started to rise. Will he let me play 7...Ne4!? and can I beat another
great player in this variation!? --- Indeed, Shirov did let me play ...Ne4 and
again, I achieved a good position. Unfortunately, I played badly and failed to
convert my advantage but this was still a good result for the opening. ---
Anyway, I will let you judge for yourself...} 1. d4 e6 2. c4 f5 3. g3 Nf6 4.
Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O d6 7. Nc3 Ne4 {Let's get that move in!} 8. Qc2 {This
is White's most common reply, so Black needs to know these lines pretty well.
In all honesty, I do not think that this line offers White any advantage.} (8.
Nxe4 $1 {is the best move. We will explore this move in more detail later on.})
8... Nxc3 9. bxc3 {A slightly offbeat move. White compromises his pawn
structure in order to make a quick break with either e4 or d5. Black's
position seems perfectly fine after this move, though.} (9. Qxc3 a5 {will be
looked at later on in the book.}) 9... Nc6 $1 {This move is pretty much forced,
otherwise White will play e4 with an advantage.} 10. e4 {BRAINSTORMING POINT!
--- When White plays e4, Black should normally try to respond in one of two
ways: 1) Black should play ...f4. This is not possible here due to Bxf4. --- 2)
Black should play ...e5 to gain active play in the centre. This works out well
in this position. --- 10 e4 may even be slightly dubious because of Black's
response.} e5 (10... fxe4 11. Qxe4 {is the kind of position that Black must
avoid at all costs.}) 11. dxe5 dxe5 12. Rb1 $5 {This is the critical point of
the game and the move I played here was far too passive. I am sure that if
Shirov was playing Black in this position then he would have opted for a move
like ...f4!?.} a6 {It's easy to overreact when playing strong players. Black
should just carry on with his plan.} ({In actual fact, I have a number of
decent options, for example:} 12... Qe8 13. Rb5 a6 14. Rd5 Be6 15. exf5 Bxf5 $1
{with an unclear game.}) (12... b6 $5 {is interesting. The idea is to place my
bishop on c5.}) (12... f4 $5 {is another intriguing move!} 13. Rb5 Bg4 ({I
tried} 13... Bd6 14. gxf4 exf4 15. e5 Be7 16. Qe4 {in another game and
obtained a very unclear position, for example,} Qe8 17. Bxf4 Nd8) (13... fxg3
14. fxg3 Qd6 15. Rd5 Qe6 16. Be3 b6 {when Black can't be worse}) 14. Nxe5 Nxe5
15. Rxe5 f3 16. Rd1 Bd6 17. Rg5 Be6 {is unclear.}) 13. Rd1 Qe8 14. Rd5 $1 {A
typical Shirov plan!} Be6 $2 {This allows Shirov to sacrifice - not a very
wise move...} ({I am still doing well after} 14... Bf6 {and in actual fact, I
may even be better here, for example,} 15. Ba3 Rf7 (15... Be7 {with an equal
position}) 16. exf5 Be7 $1 {.}) 15. Rxb7 Bxd5 16. cxd5 {I expect that my
opponent was salivating at this point.} Na5 17. Rb1 Nc4 18. exf5 {White has
ample compensation and Shirov plays the rest of the game perfectly.} Bf6 19.
Nd2 Nd6 (19... Nxd2 20. Bxd2 Rb8 21. Rxb8 Qxb8 22. c4 {is no improvement for
Black.}) 20. c4 Qh5 21. c5 $1 {Another strong move. After the game, Shirov
mentioned that at this point, he had already calculated all the variations
leading to the end of this game!} Qxf5 22. Qxf5 Nxf5 23. d6 cxd6 (23... Ra7 {
was just too ugly.}) (23... Rac8 24. Bd5+ Kh8 25. Be6 {and White is winning.})
24. Bd5+ Kh8 25. Bxa8 Rxa8 26. g4 {The rest of the game requires little
explanation.} Nd4 27. cxd6 Bg5 28. Kf1 Rc8 29. d7 Rd8 30. Nc4 Bxc1 31. Rxc1 Kg8
32. Nxe5 Kf8 33. Rd1 1-0

