{This is a recent game that I have played in the modern 7...Ne4 variation. My
opponent was the very strong Polish GM, Krasenkow. It was clear that he had
prepared something by the speed at which he was playing his opening moves, yet
I was still able to get an advantage from the opening.} 1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 f5 3.
g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6 7. Nc3 Ne4 {I now seem to play this
variation quite regularly against players who are higher-rated than me. This
is because I am struggling to find an advantage for White in any line, but
often the positions can become quite equal, meaning there is a high percentage
chance of a draw. --- BRAINSTORMING POINT! --- This capture is the critical
variation. In my opinion this is the move that White should be looking at
whilst searching for a way to gain an advantage from the opening. As this
position is so critical I would suggest that you spend a good amount of time
taking a look at all the variations branching off from this position.} 8. Nxe4
fxe4 9. Ne1 {I still consider this a side line. In my opinion 9 Nd2 is much
more of a test for Black's opening set up.} (9. Nd2 d5 10. f3 Nc6 11. fxe4
Rxf1+ {is looked at in the theory section.}) 9... d5 10. f3 {The disadvantage
that White faces in this variation is the placement of his queen and some
potential tactical problems on the d-file.} dxc4 {Aiming to play a plan based
around ...e5 or ...c5, when we see why White's queen on d1 is badly placed.} (
10... Nc6 {is another option, and it also looks OK for Black. For example,} 11.
fxe4 $1 {as we have seen in a number of examples, this is often the correct
way to continue;} (11. Be3 Bg5 (11... Na5 $5 {maybe an improvement}) 12. Bxg5
Qxg5 13. f4 Qf6 {was equal in C.Moran-L.Trent, Bunratty 2013}) 11... Rxf1+ 12.
Bxf1 dxe4 $1 (12... dxc4 $6 13. e3 {is slightly better for White, as the black
pawn on c4 is in trouble; this is the one occasion when capturing on e4,
rather than c4 seems correct}) 13. e3 e5 $5 14. d5 Nb8 15. Bg2 Bf5 16. Qc2 Bb4
17. Bd2 Bxd2 18. Qxd2 Nd7 {, with a roughly equal position.}) 11. fxe4 {The
most logical move.} ({A suggestion of English GM Glenn Flear is} 11. Be3 $5 {
which Glenn had prepared against me for one game, yet when I played 11...Nf6 I
was the player who got the first surprise in!} Nd7 $5 {is a move that Glenn
does not mention, but it seems like quite a good choice. For example,} 12. fxe4
(12. Qc2 Nf6 13. Qxc4 Nd5 $1 {is a nice manoeuvre:} 14. Nc2 b5 $1 15. Qb3 (15.
Qxb5 $2 {loses to} Nxe3 16. Nxe3 Qxd4) 15... exf3 16. Rxf3 Rxf3 17. Bxf3 Qd7 {
planning ...Bb7 with an equal position}) 12... Rxf1+ 13. Bxf1 Nf6 (13... c5 $5
{is another decent option:} 14. Nf3 Qb6 15. Qc2 cxd4 16. Bxd4 Qc7 {is equal})
14. e5 Ng4 $5 15. Bf4 g5 16. e4 h5 {(a crazy line!)} 17. h3 gxf4 18. hxg4 fxg3
19. gxh5 Kh8 20. Bxc4 b5 21. Bxb5 Rb8 {with a mess!}) 11... Rxf1+ {This does
move White's light-squared bishop to f1, where it is quite well placed. On f1
it puts pressure on the black pawn on c4. 11...Rxf1 is not a mistake though,
it is my follow-up plan that makes this idea dubious.} (11... e5 $5 {is
interesting.} 12. e3 Bf6 (12... b5 $5 13. a4 b4) 13. Nf3 Bg4 {and now} 14. Qa4
{would have given White an advantage in J.Pinter-H.Thanh Trang, Hungarian
League 2010.}) 12. Bxf1 e5 $6 {Aiming for maximum activity as now the
light-squared bishop on c8 has chances to enter the game.} ({This is not the
most accurate move though, and a much better and safer plan would have been} 
12... c5 $1 {.} 13. -- ({. This move looks like a good way of reaching
equality, for example:} 13. d5 Bf6 {(this is a nice diagonal for the
dark-squared bishop)} 14. Qa4 c3 15. bxc3 Bxc3 16. Bg5 $1 Qd7 17. Qxd7 Nxd7 18.
Rc1 Bb2 19. Rc2 Bf6 20. Bxf6 Nxf6 21. e5 Nxd5 22. Rxc5 b6 {with an equal game.}
) ({. Another line after 12...c5 is} 13. e3 Nc6 {(keeping the pressure up
against d4)} 14. Nf3 Bf6 {and now White has a couple of options:} 15. -- (15.
d5 {(this seems to be the critical test, but again there is little danger to
Black's position)} exd5 16. Qxd5+ (16. exd5 Be6 $1 {. This is a very clever
move, which forces} 17. e4 {, when} Bg4 {followed up with ...Nd4 must give
