1. d4 f5 2. g3 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6 7. Nc3 Ne4 8. Qc2 {
This is, without a doubt, White's most natural move and I am sure that if you
play ...Ne4, you will find that a lot of your opponents will respond with Qc2.
This move forces Black to make a decision about his knight on e4 and it also
helps White to play e4 at a later stage. --- Nonetheless, Qc2 is not
disconcerting and it seems that Black will obtain a good position in most
cases.} (8. Qd3 {has little independent value as the position will normally
transpose after} Nxc3 9. Qxc3 (9. bxc3 Nc6 10. e4 e5 {and Black is at least
equal.})) 8... Nxc3 9. Qxc3 ({White can also try} 9. bxc3 {but White will
always have a problem with his c-pawns.} Nc6 {and now White can choose between:
} 10. -- (10. d5 Na5 11. -- (11. Qa4 {defends the pawn on c4 and attacks
Black's knight on a5. White has to stop Black from playing ...e5, for example,}
b6 12. dxe6 (12. Nd4 e5 13. Nc6 Bd7 $1 14. Nxd8 Bxa4) 12... Bxe6 13. Nd4 Bxc4
14. Nc6 (14. Bxa8 Qxa8 {gives Black good compensation on the light squares})
14... Qd7 15. Nxe7+ Qxe7 16. Bxa8 Rxa8 {.}) (11. Nd4 e5 12. Ne6 Bxe6 13. dxe6
c6 {.}) (11. dxe6 Nxc4 $1 12. Nd4 d5 13. Nxf5 Bxe6 14. Nxe7+ Qxe7 15. e4 Qc5 {
is equal.})) (10. e4 e5 {takes us back to Shirov-Williams which we looked at
in the chapter introduction. --- Since that game I have had one more outing in
this variation, when again I got a good position from the opening. Here is
that game: D.Haydon-S.Williams, British League 2013:} 11. d5 {(closing the
centre can only benefit Black, as now White will always have extremely weak
c-pawns)} Na5 {(Black is slightly better)} 12. exf5 Bxf5 13. Qe2 Qe8 14. Nd2
Qa4 15. Be4 b6 16. h4 Rf7 17. Bxf5 Rxf5 18. Qe4 Raf8 19. Kg2 Nb7 20. Nb3 Qe8
21. Be3 a5 22. Bg5 Bxg5 23. hxg5 Qg6 24. f3 Qxg5 25. Rh1 R8f7 26. Rh4 Rf4 27.
Rxf4 Rxf4 28. Qe3 Qg6 29. Rh1 h5 30. Rxh5 Qxh5 {½-½})) 9... a5 $1 {It is a
good idea to stop White from playing b4 as this move helps him to gain space
on the queenside. The move ...a5 also allows Black to obtain control of the
b4-square, for example, if White plays Re1, Black can reply with ...Bb4 at
some point. Moskalenko gives the move 9...a5 as dubious, but I have to
disagree with him on this point. He prefers 9...Bf6 but the move 10 b4 has
always scared me here. In my first book on the Dutch, Play the Classical Dutch,
I suggested the move 10...Nd7, but nowadays I prefer not to give my opponent
so much space on one area of the board. --- In my opinion, White's trickiest
moves are 10 Qc2 and 10 b3. 10 b3 is a very popular choice so Black should be
well prepared against this variation.} 10. -- ({a)} 10. Qc2) ({b)} 10. b3) *

