1. d4 f5 2. g3 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6 7. Nc3 Ne4 8. Qc2
Nxc3 9. Qxc3 a5 $1 10. b3 {. --- BRAINSTORMING POINT! --- Many players will
choose to play b3 in this position as it is a very natural move that helps
White to complete his development. In some cases, White will aim for a small
edge in an ending. What should Black's plan be? --- The plan we are about to
look at is very important as it appears in several positions and is an idea
that you should remember...} Nc6 $1 11. Bb2 Bf6 $1 {Black is preparing to play
...e5 and there is nothing that White can do to stop it.} 12. Qd2 ({Or} 12.
Rad1 Qe8 $1 13. Qd2 {. --- BRAINSTORMING POINT! --- If it was White to play in
this position then the move d5! would be good as it destroys Black's pawn
structure. However, it is Black to play. What move should Black play here?} e5
$1 {Of course! O.Gladyszev-R.Pert, Montpellier 2003, now continued} 14. dxe5
dxe5 15. e4 f4 $5 {(a typical plan) and Black was doing well.}) 12... e5 13.
dxe5 dxe5 14. Qd5+ $1 {The black king is pushed offside which can only help
White in the endgame.} Kh8 15. Qxd8 Rxd8 16. Rfd1 {BRAINSTORMING POINT! ---
Black must watch out for the following plan: Rfd1, Ne1, Bxc6, Nd3 and then Nc5.
--- I originally studied this position with the Pert twins, who thought that
this was a good way for White to obtain a small but safe advantage. In actual
fact, this position can be quite dangerous for Black but with accurate play,
Black should be doing fine. --- White plans to move the knight on f3 to e1,
exchange on c6 and then plant the knight on c5. Black has a number of
interesting options here. --- BRAINSTORMING POINT! --- I will list all of
Black's sensible options, but if you are in a rush then a general rule is the
following: 1) Play ...Re8 if you are trying to win. --- 2) Play ...Rf8 if you
are happy with a draw.} -- {Black's available options are:} (16... Rf8 {This
has the idea of playing ...e4 and then capturing the bishop on f6 with the
rook to avoid being given doubled f-pawns.} 17. Ne1 e4 $1 {(Black should play
this move before White's knight can reach the active d3-square)} 18. Bxf6 Rxf6
{(with an equal position)} 19. f3 {(White must use this break to activate his
light-squared bishop)} Re6 $6 (19... exf3 $1 {was a lot simpler, for example,}
20. exf3 f4 $5 21. Nd3 g5 {is equal}) 20. Nc2 Re8 (20... exf3 21. Bxf3 Re8 22.
Ne3 $1 {and White is better}) 21. Nd4 $2 (21. fxe4 fxe4 22. Ne3 {with a big
advantage to White}) 21... exf3 22. Bxf3 Nxd4 23. Rxd4 c6 24. Re1 {½-½ S.Knott-S.Williams, British Championship 2005.}) (16... Rg8 $5 {I played this
strange move on one occasion, but I expect that it is rather too imaginative.
The idea is to take advantage of the open g-file at a later stage. For example,
} 17. Ne1 e4 {(I wanted to play this advance before my opponent had a chance
to play Nd3)} 18. Rab1 $6 {Black has no difficulties after this move.} ({White
should have played} 18. Bxf6 gxf6 19. Nc2 $1 {which looks to be a bit better
for him. His knight has a nice route into the centre via e3 and d5.} ({Or} 19.
f3 f4 $1 {[this was the point behind 16...Rg8!?]} 20. gxf4 exf3 21. Nxf3 Bh3
22. Nh4 Rxg2+ 23. Nxg2 Rg8 24. Rd3 $1 Bxg2 25. Rg3 Be4 {with a roughly equal
ending})) 18... a4 19. f3 axb3 20. axb3 Ra2 21. Bxf6 gxf6 22. Kf1 Re8 (22... f4
$5 23. gxf4 e3) 23. fxe4 fxe4 {. The position is equal, R.Abayasekera-S.Williams, English Border League 2005.}) (16... e4 {This looks OK for Black.}
17. Rxd8+ (17. Bxf6 $2 Rxd1+ 18. Rxd1 exf3 {and Black will win material}) ({or
} 17. Ne5 $6 Rf8 18. Nxc6 Bxb2 {, and again Black is doing well}) 17... Bxd8
18. Nd4 Bf6 19. Rd1 Bxd4 20. Bxd4 Nxd4 21. Rxd4 Be6 22. f3 exf3 23. Bxf3 c6 {
, with an equal game.}) (16... Be6 {This is the most logical way to play
against White's set-up but it may not be the best solution.} 17. Ne1 $1 {(this
retreat is very annoying; as always, the threat is Bxc6 and Nd3-c5)} e4 (17...
Rxd1 {also looks very sensible;} 18. Rxd1 Rd8 {was S.Johann-R.Forthofer,
Oberliga Sued 2010, but White can claim an edge after} 19. Rxd8+ Nxd8 20. e4 $1
) 18. Bxf6 gxf6 19. f3 $1 {and White is slightly better.}) (16... Re8 $1 {This
may be the best move. --- BRAINSTORMING POINT! --- The rook gives extra
protection to the e5-pawn from e8 making it possible to generate quick
counterplay on the queenside with ...a4. --- The position looks equal, for
example,} 17. Ne1 a4 $1 18. Bxc6 bxc6 {(Black is planning to play 19...Rb8 on
his next move and increase the pressure against b3)} 19. f4 exf4 20. Bxf6 gxf6
{with an equal game.}) *

