1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 f5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6 7. Nc3 Ne4 8. Nxe4
fxe4 9. Nd2 d5 10. f3 Nc6 11. fxe4 Rxf1+ 12. Nxf1 dxc4 13. Be3 Qd7 $6 {At
first glance, this move looks strange but it does make sense for the following
reasons: 1) Black keeps the pressure against d4. --- 2) Black plans to play ...Rb8 and ...b5. The queen on d7 conveniently defends the Black knight on c6.
--- 3) Eventually Black wants to fianchetto his light-squared bishop. --- I
would suggest that you only use this as a surprise weapon though.} 14. e5 {
This is quite a logical reply as White wants to increase the pressure along
the a8-h1 diagonal and in some cases, threaten to play d5.} ({White's other
options include:} 14. d5 Ne5 15. Bd4 (15. Bh3 Qe8 {looks fine for Black}) 15...
Nf7 $1 (15... Ng4 $5) 16. Qc2 b5 17. a4 c6 {. This is Albrecht's analysis from
the Chess Publishing forum. I have to admit it that the analysis looks good as
Black has a decent position.}) (14. Nd2 $1 {This is the move that I would be
most afraid of, and it does make ...Qd7?! look slightly dubious:} Nxd4 15. Nxc4
c5 16. Bf4 $1 {. This is a good square for the bishop and White also has ideas
of playing e3. I expect that White has a small advantage here, for example,}
Qb5 $5 (16... g5 {is suggested by my computer but Black's king just looks too
exposed!}) 17. b3 e5 $5 {(attempting to sacrifice a pawn to bring the
light-squared bishop to life)} 18. Bxe5 Bg4 19. Bxd4 cxd4 {and White has a
healthy extra pawn.}) 14... Rb8 ({Unfortunately, Black cannot play} 14... b5 $2
{due to} 15. d5 {, which wins material.}) 15. d5 (15. Rc1 {is another line
that "Mouse slip" suggests on the Chess Publishing forum. His analysis is as
follows:} b5 16. d5 Nxe5 17. Qd4 Bd6 18. Qxa7 c6 {.}) 15... Nxe5 ({"Mouse
slip" now provides us with the following interesting analysis:} 15... Nb4 $1
16. dxe6 Qxd1 (16... Qb5 $5) 17. Rxd1 Bxe6 18. Bxa7 Ra8 19. Bd4 Rd8 {. This is
the end of Albrecht's analysis and yet again I am impressed, as Black's
position is fine, for example,} 20. Rd2 b6 21. a3 Nd3 $5 22. exd3 Rxd4 23. dxc4
Bc5 $1 {. Black is currently two pawns down but the power of his bishops will
become overwhelming!}) 16. Qd4 Qd6 $2 {This is the real mistake.} ({"Mouse
slip" points out that he should have played} 16... Bd6 {with a dynamically
equal position, for example,} 17. Qxa7 (17. Nd2 $5) 17... c6 18. dxc6 Nxc6 19.
Qb6 Ra8 $1 {, "Albrecht's" idea "is to play ...Ra6 next with a good game".})
17. Bf4 Bf6 18. Qxa7 {White is clearly better now. This is a real shame as
Black had spent a lot of time preparing this line.} c6 19. dxc6 bxc6 20. Rd1 $1
{This wins material and the game.} Qxd1 21. Qxb8 Ng4 22. Qxc8+ Kf7 23. Bf3 Bd4+
24. Kg2 Qe1 25. Qd7+ {1-0 R.Stern-R.Albrecht, Berlin-Lichtenberg Open 2010.} *

