1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 f5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6 7. Nc3 Ne4 8. Nxe4
fxe4 9. Nd2 d5 10. f3 Nc6 11. fxe4 Rxf1+ 12. Nxf1 dxc4 13. Be3 Bd7 $5 {This
looks like the most logical continuation. Black develops a piece and after the
move ...b5, Black will then be able to meet a4 with ...a6, holding his
queenside pawn structure together, due to the fact that the queen now defends
the rook on a8. --- Black may also choose to re-route the light-squared bishop
with the moves ...Be8 and then ...Bh5. The position is fairly unknown so it
would be good to see some more practical examples. White has a number of
possibilities now:} 14. -- (14. Nd2 $6 {Paul Cumbers mentioned on the Chess
Publishing forum that this move is probably a mistake due to:} Nxd4 $1 {A nice
tactical shot. For example:} 15. Bxd4 Ba4 $1 16. Qxa4 Qxd4+ 17. Kh1 Qxd2 18.
Qxc4 Qxb2 19. Qxe6+ Kh8 20. Rf1 Bd6 (20... Bf6 $5 {was also interesting}) 21.
e5 Qxe2 22. Qd5 Qxe5 23. Qxb7 {The most likely result seems to be a draw here,
but White has had to play some accurate moves and Black was never in danger.})
(14. Bh3 $5 {Another interesting suggestion from Paul Cumbers. By placing the
bishop on this square, White applies pressure to Black's pawn on e6. With
correct play Black seems to be OK:} e5 $6 {Making a break for freedom looks
very logical,} ({but other moves worth investigating include} 14... Be8) ({and
} 14... Qe8) 15. Bxd7 Qxd7 16. d5 ({if White tries} 16. dxe5 {, Black should
play} Rd8 $1) 16... Na5 17. Bd2 $5 Qb5 18. Kg2 Rf8 {Black's knight is out of
play but White has a slightly weakened kingside, due to the exchange of
light-squared bishops.} 19. Bc3 Bc5 20. Kh1 b6 $5 {Black's knight on a5 is
coming back into the game via b7 and d6. The position is dynamically equal.}) (
14. Bf2 {White's bishop is often quite exposed on e3, so this is a useful move
to play. Black should now start typical play on the queenside: BRAINSTORMING
POINT! --- Black must gain active play on the queenside in this variation as
the queenside is where Black has the pawn majority. The normal way for Black
to do this is by playing ...b5, ...Rb8, ...Na5/...Nb4 and ...Bc6. Remember
this plan!} b5 $1 15. e5 Rb8 {Black is doing great.}) (14. e5 {This is a
logical idea. The fact that I have faced this move three times (with a 100%
score!) also tends to suggest that you are likely to encounter 14 e5. It now
seems that Black has two decent ways of proceeding. I will give both
variations, as it is always nice to have choices in life (and on the
chessboard).} -- (14... Be8 $5 {We saw this move being used in my introductory
game against Kojima. ...Bd7 and ...Be8 is a plan often seen in the French.
Black should have nothing to worry about here. I have to admit that I consider
this move to be stronger than 14...Rb8, for example:} 15. Be4 ({or} 15. Rc1 b5
16. b3 Ba3 17. bxc4 $5 ({other moves leave Black with a better position - take
a look at my game against Kojima for} 17. Rc2) 17... Bxc1 {. White has
compensation for the exchange but nothing more. We took a look at this in one
of the introductory games to this chapter. I suggest you go over that game to
get a better understanding of this variation}) 15... Bg6 $5 {Destroying the
pawn formation in order to take control of the d5-square.} ({It is worth
pointing out that} 15... Qd7 $5 {is also interesting, with the idea of playing
...Rd8 next}) 16. Bxg6 hxg6 17. Nd2 Qd5 18. Nf3 Qe4 {. With an equal game.}) (
14... Rb8 {I tried this idea twice in 2011, with a 100% success rate. For
example:} 15. Rc1 ({the other move tried against me was} 15. Be4 Nb4 16. a3 $2
({I was more concerned about} 16. Qb1 {which I consider to be critical}) 16...
Bc6 17. Qb1 Bxe4 18. Qxe4 Nd5 19. Bf2 Qe8 20. Qg4 Qf7 21. e4 Rf8 22. Qe2 Nb6
23. Nd2 Bg5 24. Be3 Bxe3+ 25. Qxe3 Qh5 26. Kg2 Rd8 27. Rc1 c5 28. dxc5 Rd3 29.
Qf2 Nd7 30. Rxc4 $4 Nxe5 31. Rd4 Ng4 32. Rxd3 Qxh2+ {0-1 G.Lock-S.Williams,
Sunningdale 2011}) 15... b5 16. a3 Na5 17. d5 Nb3 18. Rc3 Bc6 $1 19. Bxa7 Ra8
20. Bf2 Bxd5 21. e4 Bb7 22. Qg4 Ra6 {I was clearly better and managed to
convert my advantage in the game J.L.Chabanon-S Williams, French League 2011.})
) (14. Rc1 {This seems like a logical move but it does also encourage Black to
continue in standard fashion with ...b5, etc.} b5 {This is certainly the move
to play as I no longer have to worry about a4. Originally, I assumed that
White's central pawn formation would always be stronger than Black's queenside
pawn majority, but this is not always the case, as shown in the game.} 15. e5 {
A very logical idea. The first time I encountered this position I now had a
moment of semi-madness...} Nb4 $6 {This move is probably unsound but I assumed
that I would always get good compensation after the exchange on a8 takes place.
White always has to be wary of his weak light squares.} ({A much safer and
possibly better option would have been to play} 15... Rb8 {, preparing to play
...Nb4 but without losing the rook on a8! (this position has actually appeared
earlier in the book). The position is roughly equal here, for example,} 16. Nd2
Nb4 (16... Bg5 $5) 17. Ne4 Nxa2 18. Ra1 Nb4 19. Rxa7 Bc6 {and the opening has
been a success}) 16. Bxa8 {The only way to refute a sacrifice is to accept it!}
Qxa8 17. a3 {White should certainly avoid losing this pawn otherwise Black's
queenside pawn majority can become deadly.} Nd5 18. Bf2 Nb6 {I have to try and
stop my opponent from playing e4, as this move would shut the long diagonal.
My knight can also be a bit of a nuisance on a4.} 19. g4 $2 {White has played
well up to this point but this is clearly the wrong plan.} ({A better idea
would have been to play} 19. Nd2 $1 {. Here, the knight controls the important
e4- and f3-squares. Play could continue} Bc6 20. e3 Bh1 21. Qf1 {and there is
no obvious way for me to continue. White also has some re-arranging to do, but
all in all, an extra exchange must count for something!}) 19... Bg5 ({I could
also have played} 19... Qe4 $5 {which is fine for Black}) 20. Ra1 $6 {Another
error.} ({White should have tried} 20. e3 {, which may still be a bit better
for him, for example,} Bc6 21. Nd2 $1 Bh1 22. Qf1) 20... Qe4 $1 21. Ng3 Qxg4
22. e4 Qxd1+ $5 {An interesting choice. I thought that the endgame would be
dangerous for White.} ({Another sensible plan would have been to play} 22...
Qf4 {, which keeps the queens on the board}) 23. Rxd1 Na4 $1 24. Rb1 {White's
minor pieces are very badly placed as they are all tied down to defending.} Bc6
$1 {Stopping the white knight from moving. Black's position is much more
favourable.} 25. d5 $5 (25. Kg2 c3 26. bxc3 Nxc3 27. Rb2 Nxe4 28. Nxe4 Bxe4+
29. Kg3 a6 {looks better for me due to the strength of my light-squared bishop}
) 25... exd5 26. exd5 Bxd5 27. Bd4 $2 {This move throws away the game as my
pawns prove to be too strong.} ({White had to try} 27. Bxa7 {when Black has an
advantage but White can still hang on, for example,} c5 28. Kf2 Kf7 29. Ke2 Ke6
{. Compared to the game, White has an extra pawn but I expect that Black is
still winning here}) 27... c5 28. Bc3 Kf7 29. Kf2 $6 (29. Nf5 {was a better
way of creating some counterplay. Black still has a big advantage after the
simple} Nxc3 30. bxc3 a6) 29... Ke6 {. The rest was easy in S.Sen-S.Williams,
Uxbridge 2010.}) (14. -- {Conclusion: Let's try and sum up what we have learnt
from the last two games. One thing is certain: there is still a lot of room
for improvement for both sides. --- The current evidence suggests that 13...Bd7 is fine for Black. This move is better than 13...Qd7, which runs into
problems when White replies with 14 Nd2. White may even have to start looking
for an advantage at an earlier moment with 12 Kxf1!? Only time can tell!}) *

