the fact that he has more space, but the position is still very balanced, V.Slezka-S.Pakosta, Klatovy 1994.}) 13... Bf6 14. Bb2 {BRAINSTORMING POINT! ---
How should Black start an attack?} f4 $1 {A good move! Black gets straight to
the point.} 15. Rb1 (15. gxf4 {destroys White's kingside pawn formation and
Black must be doing well after the thematic} Qe8 {.}) 15... fxg3 16. hxg3 {
Black's knight on g4 is a permanent guest as White can no longer play h3.} Qe8
$1 {Any player who understands the Classical Dutch will always be itching to
play this move! 17...Qh5 and 18...Qh2# is a hard plan to stop!} 17. Ne4 {It is
not easy to suggest an alternative plan for White.} Qh5 18. Re1 {Trying to
make an escape route for White's king, but too little too late!} (18. Nxf6+ {
is met by} Rxf6 $1 {when Black brings another piece into the attack. This
really is a dream Dutch position!}) 18... Qh2+ 19. Kf1 Be5 {Black had a number
of promising ideas but this one does the job, as White quickly falls apart.}
