{Let's now move onto the most critical choice and the reason why I would not
want to play 7...Nc6 on a regular basis!} 1. d4 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. c4
Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O d6 7. Nc3 Nc6 8. d5 Ne5 9. Nd4 Nxc4 10. Nxe6 {This is
very logical. White exchanges Black's light-squared bishop in order to weaken
some key squares, namely b7.} Bxe6 11. dxe6 c6 $1 {Black needs to take control
of some central squares.} 12. Qd3 $1 {This is the most critical variation.
White aims to capture the Black pawn on f5.} (12. e4 {was played in the game R.Tuominen-J.Pessi, Tampere 1992. Black had nothing to fear and should have
gained an equal position after} fxe4 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 (13... d5 {is also
interesting}) 14. Bxe4 d5 15. Bd3 {. However, Black now continued} Rf6 $6 {
which looks a bit suspicious.} ({He should instead have played} 15... Bd6 $1 {
which allows Black's queen to move to either e7 or, in some cases, f6.})) 12...
d5 13. Qxf5 {This is possibly the most important position to look at when
evaluating the move 7...Nc6!?. --- Black has a number of options here but in
practice, he has only ever played 13...Ne4. --- Let's take a look at the
alternatives. Some of them are tricky, but if White is well-prepared then he
should not have any difficulties.} -- (13... Ne4 14. Qh3 (14. Qg4 {was the
move played in E.Najer-S.Gavritenkov, Krasnodar 1997. That game continued} Nxc3
{,} ({but} 14... Nf6 {is an improvement, for example,} 15. Qd4 Qd6 16. e4 $1 c5
17. Qd1 d4 18. Nd5 {, although White still has the better position})) 14... Ng5
{.} (14... Nxf2 15. Rxf2 Bc5 16. e3 Rxf2 17. Kxf2 Qg5 18. Nd1 Re8 {. White has
a clear advantage.}) (14... Nxc3 {. The simplest way for White to gain an
advantage here is to play} 15. bxc3 Bf6 (15... Qa5) 16. Rb1 b6 17. e4 Bxc3 18.
exd5 cxd5 19. Rb5 d4 20. Rh5 h6 21. Bxh6 gxh6 22. Qg4+ Qg5 23. Rxg5+ hxg5 24.
Qxg5+ Kh8 25. e7 Rfe8 26. Qh6+ Kg8 27. Bd5# {1-0 M.Roiz-E.Aponte Castillo,
Playchess.com 2004.})) (13... Bb4 {Black's bishop is well placed on b4 as it
threatens to swap off the knight on c3, making it harder for White to play e4.}
14. Qd3 {(White prepares e4)} Qe8 15. e4 $1 Bxc3 16. Qxc3 Qxe6 17. exd5 cxd5
18. Re1 Qf7 19. Qd4 {. White is clearly better as he has the bishop pair.
Furthermore, Black's pawn on d5 may become weak at a later stage.}) (13... Qb6
14. Qc2 (14. b3 $2 {is a mistake due to} Ne4 $1 {and Black should be winning})
14... Rae8 {(Black plans to move the bishop on e7 and then capture the pawn on
e6)} 15. e4 {is a simple way for White to gain an advantage.} d4 16. Nd1 Ne5
17. f4 $5 {. White is better.}) (13... Bd6 14. Qc2 $1 {. As usual, White aims
to play e4. Black's options are simply not good enough, for example:} -- (14...
Qe7 15. e4 {.}) (14... Qe8 15. b3 Ne5 16. e4 d4 {.}) (14... b5 15. e4 $1 Qe7 ({
or} 15... d4 16. Ne2 {and White is going to win a pawn}) 16. exd5 Nxd5 17. Nxd5
cxd5 18. Qd3 {. Yet again, White has a big advantage.})) (13... Bc5 $5 {This
is the trickiest move for White to meet. The bishop takes aim at f2 and as a
result, White always has to be wary of ...Ne4.} 14. b3 $1 {seems to be White's
best response, so we will concentrate on this move:} -- (14... Nb6 {(the
knight is well placed on b6 and the d6-square is left open for Black's bishop)}
15. Qc2 {(this is the standard manoeuvre)} Qe7 {(This is the main difference
between 14...Nb6! and 14...Nd6?!. The black queen can now defend the
dark-squared bishop on c5. However, Black's position is still bad.)} 16. Bh3 {
. White tries to hold onto his e6-pawn. It is very hard for Black to win the
pawn back, so White must be better, for example,} Rad8 17. Bb2 Ba3 18. Bxa3
Qxa3 19. Rad1 {.}) (14... Ne4 $2 {(this natural move is actually a mistake)}
15. e7 $1 {(a very good move that vacates the e6-square for White's queen and
leaves White with a big advantage)} Qxe7 (15... Bxe7 16. Qe6+ {and White is
winning}) 16. Nxd5 $1 {is the point behind White's play.}) (14... Nd6 {also
looks sensible. From d6, the knight gives extra protection to the e4-square,
therefore making it harder for White to achieve the e4 advance. However after
Qc2, Black's dark-squared bishop on c5 does feel a little vulnerable.} 15. Qc2
$1 {is the best square for White's queen.} Bb6 {is the most sensible option
but with accurate play, it would seem that White still has the advantage, for
example,} 16. Ba3 $1 Re8 17. e4 $1 {and White is better.})) *

