{I played this game at the Montpellier Open in 2003. This was a great
tournament as the town and beach had a lot to offer! --- My opponent, a strong
player, chose a line which had become increasingly popular over the years.
Luckily, I had looked at the line with my good friend Richard Pert before the
game. Richard had suggested a very interesting idea, an idea that he had
previously used against GM Glenn Flear. Well, the idea worked a treat! Let's
take a look.} 1. d4 e6 {I normally play this as I am happy to enter into a
French Defence after 2 e4 d5.} 2. c4 f5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O
d6 (6... a5 {is another option as long as you are happy playing into the 'Ye
Olde Faithful' line which could be a problem... please refer to Chapter One of
this book! This is an interesting move order trick that also stops White from
playing b4, for example,} 7. Nc3 (7. b3 a4 $5 {is an interesting idea}) 7... d6
{and Black avoids the early b4 variations.}) 7. b4 $5 {This is a good plan.
White tries to grab some space on the queenside as well as suffocate Black on
the same side of the board.} Ne4 $1 {In previous games, we have seen that this
is a good square for Black's knight. The knight move also allows Black to play
...Bf6.} 8. Bb2 {A natural developing move.} ({Another possible idea was} 8. a4
$5 {which stops the plan chosen by Black in the game.}) 8... a5 {An attempt to
gain some counterplay on the queenside.} 9. b5 (9. a3 {will be looked at later
on in this book.}) 9... a4 $5 {A very interesting idea. This is the move that
Richard Pert had previously played and analysed. There are two main points
behind this move: 1) Black wants to make it difficult for White to develop his
knight on b1. --- 2) Black stops White from playing a4 and in doing so, limits
White's defensive resources. Black can also aim to play ...c6 and ...cxb5,
which will weaken White's pawn on b5.} 10. Nfd2 {Naturally, White wants to
swap off Black's knight on e4.} d5 $1 {This is a rare example where I am happy
to play a Stonewall Dutch set-up. My main idea is to attack White's pawns on
c4 and b5. It is also hard for White to develop his queenside pieces.} 11. Nxe4
{By capturing this knight, White can move his other knight to d2.} fxe4 {
Recapturing towards the centre is the normal response.} 12. Ba3 c6 $1 {
BRAINSTORMING POINT! --- In this variation, Black often relies on this move to
try to destroy White's pawn formation on the queenside.} 13. f3 $2 {This is a
typical move that White plays once he has captured on e4, but in this position,
the move is not so strong because I will win a pawn and gain the initiative.}
exf3 (13... dxc4 $5 {was also worth considering.}) 14. Bxf3 dxc4 15. bxc6 Nxc6
{All of a sudden, White's pawn on d4 comes under attack. Black has played
sensible developing moves and is now doing very well.} 16. e3 e5 $1 {My bishop
on c8 comes to life.} 17. d5 Nb4 {White is now in serious trouble.} 18. Nc3 Bh3
19. Bg2 Bxg2 20. Rxf8+ Qxf8 21. Kxg2 Nd3 22. Bxe7 Qxe7 {I am simply a pawn up
with the attack.} 23. Rb1 Qg5 24. Rxb7 $2 {White has a hopeless position after
this move.} Rf8 25. d6 Qxe3 26. d7 {What is the best way to finish White off?
To start with, look at all the checks and captures...} Ne1+ $1 27. Kh3 Qh6+ 28.
Kg4 Qe6+ {. White resigned as it is mate in two.} 0-1

