{This next game was played at the Hastings International Chess Congress in
2009. Hastings is the longest running tournament in the history of chess and I
have regularly competed in the congress since the age of twelve. The
tournament starts just after Christmas and Hastings itself is normally very
wet and windy, but there is warmth to be found in "The Pig in Paradise", which
is a friendly pub, where I have analysed a large number of games. --- White's
opening choice in this game is quite popular. Let's take a look.} 1. d4 e6 2.
c4 f5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nc3 O-O {BRAINSTORMING POINT! --- Black always
has to be careful in the opening as White has a number of move order tricks.
If Black continues to move in stereotypical fashion, then he can easily reach
a bad position. In other words, do not rush the opening and always be aware of
White's options.} 6. Nh3 {This has been a very popular choice since it was
recommended as an answer to the Stonewall Dutch. If Black continues with the
pawn push ...d5, then the knight on h3 will be well placed, but of course
Black does not have to play d5 here. In actual fact, if Black can play ...d6
and ...e5 then White's knight on h3 can become quite stupid. --- Let's just
see what happens in the game.} (6. e4 $6 {is now pointless as Black can play}
fxe4 7. Nxe4 d5 $1 {with a good position. More on this move later.}) 6... d6 $1
7. O-O $6 {This is the wrong plan, after which Black gains a perfectly
respectable position.} ({Later on, Greek GM Halkias played the much more
dangerous idea of} 7. Nf4 $1 {against me. This move will be looked at in the
last introductory game of this chapter.}) 7... e5 {This standard Dutch move
appears to be stronger in this position due to the fact that White's knight on
h3 is misplaced. The knight really wants to move to f4 but this is not
possible.} (7... c6 {is another sensible move. Black gains control of d5
before playing ...e5.}) 8. dxe5 {White goes for a queen exchange but this move
does not improve White's position.} dxe5 {Black is at least equal.} 9. Qxd8
Bxd8 $1 {In the majority of cases, this is the best way for Black to recapture
the queen. There are two main reasons why this is the correct move: 1) White
would like to play Nd5 which attacks the e7-square. Therefore, Black saves a
tempo by capturing on d8 with the bishop. --- 2) Black wants to play ...c6 and
then ...Bb6. If White eventually plays e4 then Black's bishop will be
excellently placed on d4, as it cannot be kicked away from this square. The
a7-g1 diagonal is better than the f8-a3 diagonal!} 10. Ng5 {In the next
introductory game, we will look at another option for White. --- White has to
waste time in order to bring this knight back into the game.} ({Other moves
would allow me to play ...h6, when the knight is stuck on h3, for example,} 10.
b3 h6 $5 11. Ba3 Re8 {looks good for Black.}) 10... c6 {This move controls d5
and allows me to play ...Bb6 or maybe ...Ba5. I think that Black is slightly
better here.} 11. b3 {BRAINSTORMING POINT! --- White wants to play Ba3 and Nf3.
How can I try and stop White from doing this?} e4 $1 {Taking control of f3.
White's knight is now cut off.} 12. h4 ({White had to play this move otherwise
I would have played ...h6 and ...g5, when White's knight is permanently
stranded, for example,} 12. Rd1 h6 13. Nh3 g5 {.}) 12... Na6 {It is time to
develop!} 13. Bf4 h6 {This move looks fine for Black. White's knight really
wants to move to f4 but now this plan will take a lot longer.} 14. Nh3 Be6 {
White's bishop on g2 and knight on h3 are very badly placed. The only way that
White can activate them is to play f3. As a result, I should try and stop this
move at all costs or, if I cannot prevent it, then I should at least aim to
make this move less effective.} 15. Rfd1 Ba5 {This gains a tempo and I can now
contest the d-file.} 16. Rac1 Rad8 17. Na4 Bb4 {It is a good idea to stop a3
and Bd6.} 18. Be5 Ng4 19. Bd4 c5 20. Bb2 {BRAINSTORMING POINT! --- White is
now hoping to play Nf4 and then possibly Nd5. The whole game has revolved
around stopping White's knight on h3 from ever finding a good square. How can
Black prevent Nf4?} Bd2 $1 21. Ra1 (21. Rc2 $6 {is the move that White wants
to play but I can now get a good position through tactical means:} Be3 $1 22.
Rxd8 Rxd8 23. fxe3 Rd1+ 24. Bf1 Rxf1+ 25. Kxf1 Nxe3+ {and I will be a pawn up,
when my position is close to winning.}) 21... b6 {This move overprotects my
pawn on c5. Now my knight on a6 is free to move.} 22. Bc3 $1 {This is a good
move. White must exchange my active bishop on d2.} (22. Nf4 $2 Bxf4 23. gxf4 {
leaves White with a horrible pawn formation on the kingside. The bishop on g2
also plays no part in the game.}) 22... Bxc3 23. Nxc3 e3 $5 {This is an
interesting way of troubling White's kingside. On the downside, I am setting
free White's light-squared bishop.} 24. f3 Nf6 {This square is preferable to
e5, as I need to cover the d5-square with as many pieces as possible. I really
have to stop White from cementing a piece on d5.} 25. Nf4 {White's knight has
reached f4 but I plan to play ...g5 at some point to push this knight back.}
Bf7 26. Nb5 $2 ({Far too greedy} 26. Bh3 {was an improvement.}) 26... Nb4 $1
27. Nxa7 g5 {White's pieces are passive in comparison to Black's.} 28. hxg5
hxg5 29. Nh3 {The knight retreats to this passive square. At least White is
now attacking my pawn on g5.} Nc2 $6 {A mistake.} ({I should have played} 29...
Nh5 $1 30. Kh2 f4 {with the advantage.}) 30. Rab1 {White returns the favour!} (
30. Nc6 $1 {was the best move and White is doing fine, for example,} Ra8 31.
Rac1 Rxa2 32. Nxg5 f4 {and the position remains unclear.}) 30... Nd4 {Now
White is in serious trouble. All of his minor pieces are very badly placed.}
31. Bf1 Nh5 32. Nb5 g4 33. Ng5 gxf3 {White's kingside now falls apart.} 34.
Nxd4 f2+ 35. Kg2 cxd4 36. Nf3 f4 $1 37. Rxd4 Rxd4 38. Nxd4 Nxg3 39. Rc1 Kg7 {
White cannot stop my plan of ...Rh8, ...Rh1 and ...Rg1+.} 40. a4 Rh8 41. Nc2
Nxf1 42. Rxf1 Bh5 {This stops White from playing Kf3.} 43. Nd4 Kf6 {. White
resigned in view of ...Rg8+ and ...Ke5. --- As you can see, a large portion of
this game was spent preventing White's knight on h3 and bishop on g2 from
entering the game. Without these two pieces, White will find it hard to ever
claim any advantage.} 0-1

