{It may be slightly inappropriate to include this game as it was played in a
blitz competition but I do think that it demonstrates the potential of Black's
position even after the queens have been exchanged. Please do not be too
critical about the moves as the game was played at a time limit of three
minutes each plus two seconds a move. For this reason, I have not analysed the
game in too much detail. --- On the plus side, it is another victory for the
Classical Dutch against a 2700+ player!} 1. c4 f5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 e6 4. Bg2
Be7 5. d4 O-O 6. Nh3 {This idea is surprisingly popular among top players, and
it may well become the latest trend. Do not fear though, we cover everything
deeply in this chapter!} d6 $1 {Black's idea is to play ...e5 when White's
knight on h3 will look completely out of place.} 7. O-O $6 {Just as in the
previous game, White makes a typical mistake. After 7 0-0 White's knight on h3
remains a bad piece.} (7. Nf4 $1 {is critical and is examined in the next game.
}) 7... e5 $1 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Qxd8 Bxd8 $1 {BRAINSTORMING POINT! --- This is
normally the correct way to recapture on d8. The two main reasons for this are
as follows: 1) White often plans to play Nd5, but now this move is less
effective as the knight on d5 does not actually attack anything. --- 2)
Black's main plan is to play ...c6 and then ...Bb6/a5 when the bishop will
become a force to be reckoned with. This is precisely what happens in the game.
} 10. b3 c6 {Black is already slightly better here in view of the following: 1)
The strong central pawns on e5 and f5. --- 2) Control of the d5-square. --- 3)
White's misplaced knight on h3.} 11. Ba3 Re8 12. Rad1 Na6 13. e4 Ba5 14. Bb2 h6
$1 {BRAINSTORMING POINT! --- This is often an important point to remember. The
main idea of ...h6 is to stop White's knight from re-entering the game via g5.}
15. exf5 Bxf5 16. f3 Bb6+ {Another important concept. After White has played
e4, Black wants to place his bishop on the most active square, namely d4.} 17.
Nf2 Nb4 {Black's pieces are very active. White must proceed with extreme
caution!} 18. Na4 Be3 19. Bc1 $2 {This move is too passive.} ({I think that
White should have tried} 19. Rfe1 $5 {with the idea of sacrificing the
exchange and gaining activity after} Bxf2+ 20. Kxf2 Nd3+ 21. Rxd3 Bxd3 22. Bxe5
{.}) 19... Bd4 20. Bb2 Bxb2 21. Nxb2 Nxa2 {Winning a pawn and retaining a
positional advantage. The rest of the game should be fairly simple but this is
never the case when facing a 2700+ player!} 22. Rd2 Nb4 23. Ne4 Bxe4 24. fxe4
Rad8 25. Rfd1 Rxd2 26. Rxd2 Kf7 27. Na4 Ke7 28. Nc5 b6 29. Nb7 g6 30. c5 bxc5
31. Nxc5 Rd8 32. Rxd8 Kxd8 33. Kf2 Ke7 34. h3 Nc2 35. Bf1 Nd4 36. Bc4 Nd7 37.
Nd3 Kd6 38. Ke3 a5 39. Bf7 g5 40. Nf2 Nc5 41. Ng4 Ncxb3 42. Nxh6 a4 43. Nf5+
Nxf5+ 44. exf5 Ke7 45. Bc4 Nd4 46. Ke4 Kf6 47. h4 gxh4 48. gxh4 Nxf5 49. Ba2
Nxh4 50. Kd3 Kf5 51. Bb1 Kf4 52. Kc4 e4 53. Kb4 Nf5 54. Kxa4 Ne7 55. Kb4 e3 56.
Bd3 Kf3 57. Kc5 0-1

