{This game should have been an important moment in the development of my Dutch
Defence career. My opponent found a rather old, yet interesting idea that I
fell straight into. I went on to lose an important game, in an important team
event. --- I made a typical mistake after the game, instead of analysing my
errors, I headed straight to the bar, pushing the game into the recesses of
the mind. This meant that I lost again in similar circumstances, in future
events. One simple bit of advice: always analyse your losses! --- In my
defence, it was Christmas Day!} 1. d4 e6 2. g3 f5 3. Bg2 Nf6 4. c4 (4. Nh3 {
might be a slightly better move order. White does not need to commit the pawn
to c4 yet.}) 4... Be7 5. Nc3 {Again this may not be the most precise move
order from White, if he wants to play Nh3. As we will see in some subsequent
games, b3 is often more useful than Nc3.} (5. Nh3 $1 d6 6. b3 {is an improved
move order.}) 5... O-O (5... d6 $5 {is an interesting move order, the point
being that Black wants to avoid Nh3-f4. For example,} 6. Nh3 (6. e4 {is one
way that White can try to take advantage of this different move order. After 5...0-0 6 e4 is a bad move due to 6...fxe4 7 Nxe4 d5. This plan is less
effective now.} fxe4 7. Nxe4 O-O {should be fine for Black. The weakness on e6
is not so important as White has yet to finish his development}) 6... e5 $1 {
stopping the white knight from reaching f4. This is the type of position that
Black wants to be aiming for. Black has gained a strong centre whilst keeping
White's knight side-lined on the edge of the board.}) 6. Nh3 {At the time I
was happy to see this move, but this feeling quickly changed!} d6 7. Nf4 $1 {
I now played what seemed to be a very natural move.} e5 $2 {Assuming that
White was planning to bring his knight on f4 into d5. Black is always doing
well against this plan as Black can simply play ...c6, kicking the knight away.
Instead I was shocked by my opponent's real plan!} (7... c6 {, with ...e5 in
mind, would have been a much better plan. For example,} 8. Nd3 Nbd7 $1 {(Black
must play ...e5!)} 9. O-O e5 10. e3 Qe8 {with a standard position. White will
try to attack on the queenside, but Black has chances on the kingside. One
attacking idea that I have found works very well in these types of positions
is ...h5-h4.}) 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Qxd8 Bxd8 {Not seeing my opponent's next move,
I played the standard capture on d8. ...Bxd8 is effective against Nd5, but not
good against White's next move!} (9... Rxd8 {also looks better for White.} 10.
Nfd5 (10. Ne6 $2 {no longer works:} Bxe6 11. Bxb7 Nbd7 {and Black is clearly
better}) 10... Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Bd6 {. This seems to be just about OK for Black,
for example,} 12. c5 $2 (12. Bg5 Rd7 {and Black's position looks quite ugly; ...c6 will repair matters somewhat, but I would still prefer to be White. For
example,} 13. O-O-O Na6 (13... c6 $6 14. Ne7+ $1 Bxe7 15. Bxe7 Rxe7 16. Rd8+
Kf7 17. Rxc8 {is very bad for Black}) 14. e4 $1 c6 15. Ne3 {White is much
better}) 12... Bxc5 13. Nxc7 Bb4+ $1 14. Kf1 Rd1# {.}) 10. Ne6 $1 {My opponent
banged out this move very quickly, and what a nasty shock it was! This was the
first time that I had seen this idea and it is certainly a concept well worth
remembering.} Re8 ({I spent a lot of time analysing} 10... Bxe6 {but it does
not work.} 11. Bxb7 c6 12. Bxa8 Ba5 13. O-O Bxc4 (13... Nfd7 {with the idea of
playing ...Nb6, trapping White's bishop does not work because of} 14. Be3) 14.
Rb1 Nd5 15. Nxd5 cxd5 16. b3 {when eventually the bishop on a8 escapes.} Bxe2
17. Bxd5+ {and White has a large advantage.}) 11. Nxd8 Rxd8 {White has a small
advantage due to his bishop pair. Black has a good pawn structure in the
centre, but this pawn structure is difficult to maintain due to the dark
square weaknesses.} 12. Bg5 (12. Be3 {is also slightly better for White. For
example,} c6 13. O-O Be6 14. b3 Kf7 15. Rad1 Rxd1 16. Rxd1 Nbd7 17. Na4 a6 18.
Nb6 Re8 19. Nxd7 Nxd7 20. Bc1 a5 21. e4 g6 22. exf5 Bxf5 23. h3 h5 24. Bg5 e4
25. Kf1 Ne5 26. Ke2 Nd3 27. Ke3 b5 28. cxb5 cxb5 29. Rd2 Ne1 30. Bh1 Nf3 31.
Bxf3 exf3+ 32. Kxf3 Bxh3 {½-½ C.Ward-R.Pert, Aberystwyth 2014.}) 12... c6 {
My position is quite solid, but not what a Dutch player is looking for when
pushing the f-pawn.} 13. f4 {This maybe a bit eager, as White did not need to
change the pawn structure so quickly.} (13. O-O {is simple and good:} Be6 14.
Rad1 Na6 15. b3 {and White's bishop pair promises him an advantage.}) 13...
exf4 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. gxf4 {White has tried to change one type of advantage,
the bishop pair, into another type of advantage, doubled pawns. This should
still offer him better chances, but I should really have been able to hold
this position.} Be6 16. b3 Na6 17. Rd1 Rxd1+ 18. Kxd1 Kf7 19. Kc1 Rg8 20. Bf3
Nc5 21. Kc2 Ke7 22. e3 Rg6 (22... a5 {looks like a more natural way to play,
when I could have held the balance.}) 23. Ne2 Ne4 24. Rg1 Nf2 25. Ng3 Rh6 26.
Rg2 Ng4 27. Bxg4 fxg4 {I was certainly feeling more confident here. My pawns
have been straightened out and I even had chances of pushing my h-pawn all the
way down the board.} 28. f5 Bd7 {The only problem I do have, though, is the
placement of my rook on h6. At the moment it is stuck out of the game, and the
real battle revolves around whether this rook can enter the fight again or not.
} 29. c5 Rh3 30. Kd3 h5 31. Ke4 b6 (31... h4 {fails to} 32. Ne2 {, when Nf4 is
a strong threat.}) 32. b4 bxc5 33. bxc5 Bc8 {Aiming to defend the b7-square
from a penetrating white rook, but my position is already difficult. None of
my pieces are coordinating together, whilst White's king is very strong.} (
33... Be8 {does not help:} 34. Kf4 Bf7 35. Rb2 {.}) 34. Kf4 Ba6 35. a4 {Even
here the computer does not understand just how bad Black's position is. There
is no way back now.} Bc4 36. Rb2 a5 37. e4 Kf7 {I have nothing better to do
then sit around and wait for Santa to arrive.} 38. e5 fxe5+ 39. Kg5 Bd5 40. f6
h4 41. Rb7+ Ke8 42. Nf5 Rxh2 43. Nd6+ Kd8 44. f7 Rf2 45. Kxh4 e4 46. Rb8+ Ke7
47. Re8+ Kd7 48. f8=Q Rxf8 49. Rxf8 e3 50. Kg3 {. Ho, Ho, Ho, Merry (expletive
deleted) Christmas!} 1-0

