1. d4 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. Nh3 $5 {This was the first game where I ever
saw this idea being used - I came across it in Bellin's excellent book,
'Winning with the Dutch'. Any idea by Karpov is an idea worthy of
investigation. --- It is funny that 20 years on, I had a chance to talk to
Nigel about this game. It was just after I had lost to Halkias in the World
Cities Championship (see game above - Christmas Day!) and Nigel was my team
mate on the London team (strange as most of our team had little or no ties to
London). Halkias had used the same plan of Nh3 against me in a successful
manner. --- Nigel gave me the impression that this plan of Nh3 was well known
and a reason that he had stopped playing the Dutch. He was very dismissive of
Black's opening. Fair enough, but I was more disappointed to see him write
some negative things about my play in a later copy of New in Chess.} Be7 5. O-O
O-O {Of course Black can play into a Stonewall Dutch set-up at any moment, but
then the move Nh3 fits in very well with White's strategy. White will simply
want to continue with Nf4, Nd3, Nd2 and Nf3, when both white knights take
control of the e5-square.} 6. c4 d6 7. Nc3 $6 {In my opinion this is slightly
dubious as it allows Black the chance to play ...e5 with a good position.} (7.
Qb3 {has also previously been played by Karpov. That game continued} c6 $1 {
(often a good move in this variation, as when Black plays ...e5 he wants to
have control of the d5-square)} 8. Nc3 Na6 9. Ng5 e5 $1 10. Rd1 (10. c5+ d5 11.
dxe5 Nxc5 12. Qc2 Ng4 {is good for Black}) 10... Qe8 11. d5 h6 12. Nf3 {(A.Karpov-P.Nikolic, Reykjavik World Cup 1991) and now} cxd5 $1 {is very
comfortable for Black.}) (7. b3 $1 {is the best move and will be looked at in
more detail later on in this chapter.}) 7... Qe8 $6 ({Black should have played
} 7... e5 $1 {when the white knight on h3 is badly placed.}) 8. Nf4 g5 $6 {The
wrong pawn break. This and Black's next move is actually an old suggestion of
Paul Keres, quoted by Bellin in his book, but this was the first game in which
it had been tried at top level, and Karpov practically refutes it.} (8... Nc6 {
runs into the typical d5 break:} 9. d5 exd5 10. Ncxd5 {and White is slightly
better.}) (8... e5 $1 {(simple and correct)} 9. dxe5 dxe5 10. Nfd5 (10. Ne6
Bxe6 11. Bxb7 Nbd7 {is much better for Black}) 10... Bd8 {looks OK for Black.
Even so, I would prefer to have played 7...e5! one move earlier, as then the
white knight on h3 would not have gained access to the d5-square.}) 9. Nd3 $1 {
A good square for the white knight. From d3 the knight controls a number of
squares.} Qg6 10. f4 h6 {White has a pleasant advantage in this position.
Black is lacking any counterplay and control of central squares.} (10... g4 $6
{locks the pawn structure and White is clearly stronger in the centre of the
board. White plays} 11. Re1 {with e4 to follow.}) 11. d5 {White is strong in
the centre, so that is where he strikes!} Na6 (11... exd5 $1 {was a better try.
} 12. cxd5 Na6 {with ...Bd7 and ...Rae8 to follow. Black is still worse but at
least he can fight.}) 12. b4 $1 {Gaining space and stopping Black from playing
...Nc5.} exd5 (12... e5 {is the typical idea, but it fails here after} 13. b5
$1 Nb8 14. fxe5 {.}) 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Bxd5+ $1 {The correct way to capture on
d5. The bishop is very strong and does not deserve to be blocked in, as it
would be after cxd5.} Kh7 15. b5 $1 {Keeping things simple.} Nc5 16. Nxc5 dxc5
17. Qc2 a6 18. a4 Rb8 (18... axb5 19. cxb5 Rb8 20. a5 {is a lot better for
White. The a-pawn could well become a queen very quickly.}) 19. fxg5 $5 hxg5
20. Ra3 $5 {An interesting idea. The white rook prepares to move over to f3,
increasing the pressure on Black's position.} c6 21. Bg2 Bf6 (21... Be6 {runs
into} 22. g4 $1 {with some major threats.}) 22. Be3 $1 ({White could have also
tried to open up the position in the centre with} 22. e4 $6 {but this would
have given Black some counterplay after} Bd4+ 23. Kh1 cxb5 {.}) 22... Bd4 23.
Bxd4 cxd4 24. e3 {Simple play from Karpov. He realises that the black king
will always be slightly weak. In this game a quote of Yusupov keeps springing
to my mind: "Often the best move in the Dutch Opening is f5-f7, yet this is
never possible!" It is a good thing that this quote is not true in all cases!}
dxe3 25. Rxe3 Be6 26. g4 $5 {White has a large advantage due to the weaknesses
around Black's king. The game is effectively over.} Rbe8 (26... Rbc8 {loses
immediately to} 27. bxc6 bxc6 28. gxf5 Rxf5 29. Rfe1 $1 {.}) 27. bxc6 bxc6 28.
c5 {Locking the black pawn on c6.} (28. gxf5 $2 {is not so clear, for example,}
