{After my loss against Halkias, my opponents were getting wise to the idea of
playing Nh3. As you can see in the games here, I have a terrible record
against this plan! I am partly to blame though, as only now, in the making of
this book, have I seriously worked out a good way for Black to play.} 1. d4 e6
2. c4 f5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nh3 d6 {At least I remembered to play this
move early. Playing ...d6 before 0-0 gives Black more options, mainly the
possibility of advancing with ...e5 at an earlier moment.} 6. b3 $1 {The best
move from White. White aims to put his dark-squared bishop on b2, from where
it will directly attack the e5-square. This move makes more sense compared to
the Nc3 which we saw in the last game.} e5 $6 {I believe this to be premature
now.} ({David Eggleston demonstrated a much better plan in his game against
Neverov, which we will come to shortly. That plan was to simply castle and
then aim to play ...e5 with the help of moves such as ...Nbd7 ...Qe8 and ...Bd8. --- For example,} 6... O-O 7. Bb2 Qe8 $1 8. Nf4 Bd8 $1 {(preparing ...e5
and stopping the Ne6 plan which we saw in the last game, as now Black's queen
on e8 defends the e6-square)} 9. Nd3 Nbd7 $1 10. Nd2 e5 {with an equal
position.}) 7. Bb2 Ng4 $5 {This was my inventive idea behind playing ...e5.
Now that White has moved his dark-squared bishop, the e3-square is slightly
exposed. This makes it harder for White to kick my knight on g4 away with f3.
I will always try to meet f3 with ...Ne3. Still, I don't believe this is a
good enough plan for equality.} (7... e4 {looks logical, but I always try to
avoid setting the pawn formation like this. I like to try to keep my centre
fluid. White's pieces are well positioned to deal with this structure, with a
knight on h3 that is ready to come into f4. White is slightly better after} 8.
f3 {.}) 8. O-O ({I also repeated this same dubious plan against a strong
grandmaster with the same result. That game continued} 8. Na3 $1 {(This move
makes a lot of sense. White wants to play Nc2 covering the e3-square, then it
will be possible to play f3 kicking my knight on g4 away)} O-O 9. Nc2 {(I now
have to find a way to take the sting out of f3)} Bf6 10. Qd2 Nc6 11. e3 a5 {
(This position is not that bad for Black, but White may have a slight
advantage because he can always set up with f3 and Nf2. On the other hand, my
knight on g4 will have to move back to h6, on the edge of the board)} 12. O-O
Qe8 {(Not knowing anything better, I decided to stick with the queen swinger!)}
13. f3 Nh6 14. Nf2 g5 $6 {(As the situation in the centre has not been settled,
this push is probably premature. White may be able to open up the centre at
some point when my king will need all the pawn protection that it can get.)}
15. Bc3 a4 16. b4 Nf7 17. b5 Ne7 18. Rab1 h5 19. c5 $6 {Allowing my bishop
into a good square on e6. White should have avoided allowing me this option.} (
19. f4 $1 {is often a good way to close the kingside}) 19... Be6 20. Na3 b6 21.
dxe5 dxe5 22. Qe2 Ng6 $2 (22... Rd8 {was sensible and good}) 23. f4 $1 {(Now
my h5-pawn becomes a target, and the rest of the game goes from bad to worse.)}
Rd8 24. Qxh5 Kg7 25. fxg5 Nxg5 26. Qe2 Rh8 $2 (26... e4 $1 {was actually OK
for me}) 27. Rb4 bxc5 28. Rxa4 Bd5 29. e4 Ra8 30. Ra6 Rxa6 31. bxa6 Qa4 32.
exd5 Qxa3 33. Qd3 c4 34. Qxc4 Nf7 35. Qd3 Nd6 36. Bxe5 Qxd3 37. Bxf6+ Kxf6 38.
Nxd3 Ra8 39. Nb4 {1-0 K.Landa-S.Williams, Haguenau 2013.}) 8... O-O 9. Qd2 {
Guarding the e3-square and therefore aiming to play f3, whilst not allowing ...Ne3.} Nc6 {With an interesting idea in mind.} ({Instead,} 9... exd4 10. Qxd4
Bf6 11. Qd5+ {and due to the structure, White is going to be slightly better.
It is worth noting that this is a pawn formation that I nearly always aim to
avoid.}) 10. Bd5+ Kh8 11. f3 Ne3 $5 {How could I resist such a beautiful
idea!? Of course I should have resisted it, but temptation often gets the
better of me.} (11... Nf6 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. dxe5 dxe5 14. Qxd8 Bxd8 15. Bxe5
Re8 16. Bd4 Rxe2 {is still better for White.}) 12. Qxe3 f4 {Attacking the
queen and the knight on h3. I had assumed that I would have good attacking
chances in this position because my opponent had earlier played Bd5+ which
left some holes around the white kingside. On closer inspection the whole idea
seems rather suspect, though.} 13. Nxf4 {The only move.} exf4 14. gxf4 Nb4 {
One of my major faults is being over-optimistic, and that showed in my
assessment of this position. At the time I thought I had great attacking
chances, but the emotionless computer disagrees.} 15. Be4 d5 16. cxd5 Bh3 (
16... Bd6 {was my best chance, but we must not forget that White is three
pawns up!} 17. Nc3 Bxf4 18. Qf2 Bf5 19. Bxf5 Rxf5 20. Bc1 {(this game
certainly has some similarities with my encounter with Ipatov)} Bxc1 21. Raxc1
Nxd5 22. Nxd5 Rxd5 23. e4 Rxd4 24. Rxc7 Qxc7 25. Qxd4 {. White is better but
not by so much.}) 17. Nc3 $1 {To my opponent's credit, he did defend
incredibly well. Nearly all his moves were the computer's first choice. Last
time one of my opponents did that in a game with the Dutch, my opponent was
called Sebastian Feller. He was later accused of computer-cheating (Arbiter
please!!!!), but no such suspicions are attached to the present game!} (17. Rf2
Bd6 $1 {is very dangerous for White and could even be losing, for example,} 18.
f5 Qh4 19. Bc1 Rae8 {(all the boys are joining in the attack)} 20. Nc3 Nc2 {.
Black is a lot better.}) 17... Bd6 18. Qf2 Bxf4 (18... Bxf1 {was of course
possible, but then White has a safe and stable advantage. I wanted to keep
some form of an attack going. After} 19. Rxf1 Rxf4 20. Bc1 Rh4 21. f4 {,
White's pawn centre certainly looks rather scary.}) 19. Rfd1 c6 $2 {This was
too much.} (19... Bf5 $1 {kept the game alive.}) 20. dxc6 bxc6 21. d5 {White
is completely winning and just needs to avoid any tricks.} c5 22. Kh1 Be5 23.
Na4 Bxb2 24. Nxb2 Qf6 25. Nc4 Rae8 26. Qg3 Qh6 27. d6 $1 {A well worked-out
finish to the game.} Rxe4 28. fxe4 Nc2 29. Ne5 $1 Nxa1 30. d7 Bxd7 31. Nf7+ $1
{. A very strong finish to the game from my young Canadian opponent. This line
with ...Ng4 is certainly interesting but I do not believe that it is entirely
sound.} 1-0

