{In this game David Eggleston, playing Black, finds a good way to play against
an early Nh3. I suggest that you follow David's example here, I certainly will
in the future. The basic idea is to try and force through the e5 break. As
long as you remember to do this, then you should get a good position. Black
should set up this idea in one of two ways, depending on the situation: 1) The
way shown in this game: ...Qe8-Bd8-Nbd7 and finally ...e5. --- 2) ...c6-Qc7-e5.
} 1. d4 e6 2. c4 f5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nh3 {Here it is again.} O-O ({
Black can also start with} 5... d6 {but it makes little difference. Black will
play ...e5 but only after he has castled, which is slightly different to some
of the other games that we have seen.} 6. b3 O-O {and we are back into the
main game.}) 6. b3 d6 7. Bb2 (7. Nf4 Qe8 (7... e5 {is also possible in this
case:} 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Qxd8 Rxd8 (9... Bxd8 $2 10. Ne6 $1 {is a standard trick
that we have already seen in Halkias-Williams}) 10. Nd5 Nxd5 11. Bxd5+ Kf8 {
and with ...c6 to follow I would prefer to be Black due to the strong pawns on
e5 and f5}) 8. Bb2 {transposes to the game.}) 7... Qe8 $5 {A simple plan.
Black places the queen on its most natural square. From e8, the queen has
ideas of swinging out to h5, but more importantly, from e8 the queen helps
prepare the ...e5 advance.} (7... c6 {is another good plan. After} 8. O-O {
Black should now play} Qc7 $1 {. We analysed this in Ipatov-Williams.}) 8. Nf4
({White can also play} 8. O-O {and this looks like a more promising plan for
White. White will aim to get the knight on h3 back into the game via f2 after
either f3 or f4.} Bd8 9. Nc3 e5 10. e3 {is OK for Black, but I think that
White's position is slightly easier to play as it is very hard to generate an
attack on the kingside. For example,} h6 {. (a useful move to play, stopping
White from ever moving the knight on h3 into g5)} 11. Qc2 c6 $1 {(this is the
correct way to continue; with ...c6 Black takes control of d5 and prepares to
move the dark-squared bishop on d8 to either c7 or b6)} 12. Rad1 Na6 13. f3 Bc7
14. Nf2 {and now} f4 $5 {is interesting and certainly thematic for the
Classical Dutch!} 15. dxe5 dxe5 16. Ba3 $1 fxe3 17. Nfe4 Bb6 {when the
computer slightly prefers White after} 18. c5 {.}) 8... Bd8 $1 {This is
particularly effective when White has already played Nf4.} 9. Nd3 {Aiming to
stop Black from playing ...e5, in the spirit of the Karpov-Short game. It is
not so effective here as Black is well positioned to force through ...e5.} (9.
O-O e5 {is fine for Black.} 10. Nd3 Nc6 (10... e4 $5 11. Nf4 c6 ({or even} 
11... e3 $5 12. f3 {with a quite peculiar position})) 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. dxe5 {
(this is always going to be risky for White, as he might win a pawn but his
king will be weak)} Ng4 $1 {. White has to be careful. One mistake and his
position could fall apart, for example,} 13. exd6 $2 {(now Black can start a
thematic winning attack)} Qh5 14. h4 Bxh4 $1 15. Nf4 Qh6 16. Kg2 Bxg3 $1 17.
Kxg3 Qg5 $1 {and Black is winning.}) 9... Nbd7 10. Nd2 ({White can no longer
stop ...e5. For example,} 10. f4 e5 11. dxe5 dxe5 12. Nxe5 {(White has won a
pawn but there are some serious weaknesses along the a7-g1 diagonal,
especially e3)} Nxe5 13. Bxe5 Ng4 14. Bd4 Bf6 15. Nc3 Ne3 {with a dynamically
equal position.}) 10... e5 {The position is equal.} 11. dxe5 ({Or:} 11. O-O $6
{allows the march of the e-pawn.} e4 12. Nf4 e3 $1 {(Black has gained the
upper hand)} 13. Nf3 exf2+ 14. Rxf2 Ng4 {winning an exchange.}) (11. e3 {keeps
the tension and stops ...e4-e3.} e4 12. Nf4 c5 $5 13. O-O cxd4 14. exd4 (14.
Bxd4 Ne5) 14... g5 15. Nh3 h6 {. The position is equal.}) 11... dxe5 12. e4
fxe4 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 Nf6 15. Bg2 e4 {So far Black has been playing very
well.} 16. Ne5 c6 17. O-O Bc7 18. Qd4 Bf5 {There is nothing wrong with this
move, but it is often a good idea in the Dutch to leave the light-squared
bishop on c8 and only move it into the game via h3.} (18... Qh5 $1 {is
possible. --- Which Dutch Defence player would not want such a position!? After
} 19. f4 Bh3 {Black has the advantage.}) 19. Rae1 Rd8 {Black's position is
absolutely fine, but David eventually gets ground down by his higher-rated
opponent.} 20. Qc3 Qh5 {A little bit late.} 21. f4 Rfe8 ({The white knight on
e5 was an especially strong piece, and Black could have exchanged it straight
away, forcing a draw. For example,} 21... Bxe5 22. fxe5 (22. Qxe5 $2 Rd2 23.
Bc3 Rxa2) 22... Rd3 $1 23. Qc1 Ng4 24. h3 Rxg3 25. hxg4 Rxg2+ 26. Kxg2 Qxg4+
27. Kh2 Qh3+ 28. Kg1 Qg3+ 29. Kh1 Qh3+ 30. Kg1 Qg3+ {with a draw by perpetual
check.}) 22. b4 Bh3 23. Bxh3 Qxh3 24. Qc2 Qh6 $6 {Black is moving without
purpose, a sure way to lose to a higher-rated opponent.} (24... Qe6 {would at
least keep the queen more centralised.}) 25. Re2 Qh5 {I am sure the queen
moved to this square five moves ago!?} 26. c5 Bxe5 27. fxe5 Rxe5 {A decent
practical decision, as Black's e-pawn remains strong, but it is also clear
that Black can only fight for a draw after this move.} 28. Bxe5 Qxe5 29. Qc4+
Kh8 (29... Qd5 {was an interesting choice. Black would like to reach an ending,
as then his king could zoom into the centre.} 30. Qxd5+ cxd5 {could even be
good for Black, with two connected passed pawns.}) 30. Qf7 Qd4+ 31. Kg2 e3 32.
Qe7 {The end. As soon as Black's e-pawn drops, the game is over.} h5 33. Qxe3
Qxe3 34. Rxe3 {The rest is simple.} Rd2+ 35. Rf2 Rxf2+ 36. Kxf2 Ng4+ 37. Kf3
Nxe3 38. Kxe3 Kg8 39. Ke4 Kf7 40. Ke5 Ke7 41. h4 a6 42. Kf5 Kf7 43. a3 a5 44.
bxa5 Ke7 45. Kg6 Ke6 46. Kxh5 Kf5 47. g4+ Kf6 48. a4 1-0

