{This game was played in the last round of the 2012 Malta Open. I went to the
event in a bit of a holiday mood, and I was joined in Malta by a number of
chess-playing friends from England. There were a number of interesting moments.
One that springs to mind was a large bet that I managed to win. --- What did I
have to do? Well during a meal at a rather posh local restaurant, I had to
suddenly strip off and swim across the ocean to the other side of the harbour.
I must now apologise to everyone else at the restaurant who must have surely
been put off by this rather peculiar sight. Such a sensible tournament... ---
As this was the last round, a couple of us decided to drink a little bit of
Sangria before the game. Obviously this is not to be recommended, but it
certainly seemed to put me in a good mood for the match... --- Some very
thematic Dutch ideas are demonstrated in this game. Let's see what those ideas
are.} 1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 f5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. b3 {This is a very
sensible move. White prepares to develop his bishop to the natural b2-square.
I now continued with a standard idea.} Ne4 {There is no need to play ...d6
quite yet. In some cases I may have even played ...d5 instead, depending on
how my opponent continued.} 7. c4 Bf6 {I favour this set up of knight on e4
and bishop on f6. It maximises the potential of both pieces.} ({Another
typical plan would have been} 7... a5 {. This is similar in spirit to my game
against Gelfand. The a-pawn can cause a number of problems in White's position.
}) 8. Bb2 d6 {We have now transposed back into one of the main lines with an
early b3.} 9. Nc3 Nc6 {The black knight can safely develop to c6 as Black no
longer has to fear the pawn advance d5.} 10. e3 {Now that White has
over-protected his d4 pawn, White might be intending to continue with Nxe4.
For that reason I decided to capture on c3 first.} (10. Nxe4 {is nothing to
worry about, as after} fxe4 {the white knight on f3 does not have a good
square to retreat to.}) 10... Nxc3 11. Bxc3 Qe7 {I wanted to keep the queens
on the board. This might have been due to the after-effects of a jug of
Sangria.} ({Another sensible choice that leads to an equal position would have
been} 11... e5 12. dxe5 dxe5 13. Qd5+ Kh8 14. Qxd8 Rxd8 15. Rfd1 e4 $1 {with
equality.}) 12. b4 $1 {Very logical. White should gain some space on the
queenside.} e5 13. b5 (13. dxe5 dxe5 14. b5 Nd8 15. e4 {when} Nf7 $5 {is
possible,} ({but I was planning a typical idea:} 15... f4 {which leads to a
very murky position after} 16. gxf4 exf4 17. e5 Bg5 18. Nxg5 Qxg5 19. Kh1 {.}))
13... Nd8 14. Qb3 $6 {This is what I call an 'autopilot' move. It looks
sensible and cannot be a major mistake, but it also does little to stop
Black's build- up in the centre and kingside. White should have probably
captured on e5, opening up the d-file. This is often the best way for White to
react to ...e5.} (14. dxe5 dxe5 {leads to the variation given above.}) 14... e4
$1 {This is the start of a plan which I would advise you all to remember. In
this game it works to perfection. --- 1) Play ...e4, gaining some space on the
kingside. --- 2) Play ...g5-g4. This gains more space, but most importantly,
once my pawn gets to g4 White won't be able to break out with f3. This is the
one move that Black wants to stop. If Black stops f3, White's bishop on g2
becomes an awful piece. --- 3) Prepare an attack on the kingside. --- 4) Bring
my knight on d8 to g5 via f7. With a pawn on g5 and knight on g4, Black will
always have a very dangerous threat of ...Nf3+. --- 5) Open the h-file and
attack on the h-file. This can be done with ...h5-h4, ...Kg7, ...Rh8. --- 6)
Try to stop or hold up White's counterplay on the queenside. --- As we will
