{"You don't make progress by standing on the sidelines, whimpering and
complaining. You make progress by implementing ideas." - Shirley Chisholm} 1.
d4 f5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 {. We now move on to part three of this book. In part
two, we looked at what happens when White fianchettoes his light-squared
bishop. We will now look at what happens when White avoids this plan. --- This
idea is not seen that often at grandmaster level because... --- BRAINSTORMING
POINT! --- 1) Black is able to fianchetto his light-squared bishop with ...b6
and Bb7. --- 2) White's dark-squared bishop can often become trapped behind
the pawn structure. --- Black still has to find a way to exploit this, though.
White normally continues with f3, Bd3 and Nge2 creating a solid set-up. --- As
a general rule, Black should play ...Bb4, as White cannot meet this move with
c3 or Nd2. ...Bb4 takes control of e4 and threatens to double White's pawns.}
Nf6 {Let's take a look at some introductory games to get a better
understanding of the position.} *

