{In the London System, White plays the following sequence of opening moves: 1
d4, 2 Nf3, 3 Bf4 followed by c3, e3 and Be2/d3.} 1. -- {These systems are both
popular at club level because they are relatively easy to learn and can be
quite effective against a number of set-ups. The good news is that they do not
work well against a player who is well prepared in the Classical Dutch! ---
BRAINSTORMING POINT! --- 1) Against the Colle System (where White leaves his
bishop on c1), Black should develop his light-squared bishop to b7 in order to
gain more control of the e4-square. --- 2) Against the London System (where
White develops his bishop to f4), Black should leave his light-squared bishop
on c8 and instead concentrate on playing the e5 advance. --- We are going to
concentrate mainly on the London System as I believe that this is the biggest
threat to the Dutch. Just take a look at White's dark-squared bishop in both
of the diagrams above to understand my reasoning! (On the other hand, this
bishop can become a target for the move ...e5! More on this later...) ---
Let's start by investigating the London System (see the following game).} *

