{The Staunton Gambit is a popular opening at club level. Therefore, I would
suggest that you pay close attention to this chapter. --- There are a number
of ways that Black can respond to the Staunton Gambit, but the move 4...c6
seems like the best option for the following reasons: 1) It avoids the main
line. --- 2) It is easy to learn. --- 3) It contains an element of surprise.
--- In general, I would suggest that you select the simplest variations for
Black. There is no point over-complicating matters. --- Let's move on to the
theory section of the chapter!} 1. d4 f5 2. e4 {This pawn advance is a direct
attempt to refute the Dutch so it has to be treated with respect.} fxe4 3. Nc3
Nf6 ({A classic mistake that Black has to avoid is} 3... d5 $6 4. Qh5+ g6 5.
Qxd5 {when White will gain an easy advantage.}) 4. Bg5 {This is the main move,}
({but White does have some other options that are tricky, for example:} 4. g4
$5 h6 5. f3 d5 6. h3 $1 ({this is the best option as White is worse after} 6.
g5 hxg5 7. Bxg5 Bf5 8. Bg2 e3 $1 9. Nge2 Nc6 10. a3 e6 11. Bxe3 Bd6) 6... Nc6
7. fxe4 dxe4 8. Be3 e5 (8... e6 {is another idea}) 9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8
11. O-O-O+ Bd7 12. Bg2 Bd6 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 Nc4 15. Bd4 Bf4+ 16. Kb1 Nd2+
17. Rxd2 Bxd2 18. Nf3 {and the position is still unclear but Black should be
fine.}) (4. f3 {This move can often lead to the positions that are found in
some of the gambit lines where White plays 2 Nc3 and e4:} d5 $1 (4... exf3 5.
Nxf3 {is very dangerous for Black; White achieves good development in exchange
for one measly pawn!}) 5. fxe4 dxe4 6. Bg5 Bf5 7. Bc4 Nc6 8. Nge2 e6 9. O-O Na5
$1 {(Black should aim to swap off White's light-squared bishop)} 10. Bxf6 Qxf6
11. Bb3 Bd6 {.}) 4... c6 $5 ({I am going to recommend this rather unknown move,
because I am not too keen on the main line which continues} 4... Nc6 5. d5 Ne5
6. Qe2 $1 {. I think that this is the best move for White. On this square, the
queen has an X-ray attack on the black king which can be very important, for
example,} c6 7. O-O-O Qa5 8. f4 $1 Nf7 9. Bxf6 gxf6 10. Qxe4 Bg7 11. Nge2 e6
12. f5 {and White has an advantage.}) 5. f3 Qa5 $1 {I like this
counterattacking move as it puts White on the defensive.} ({A greedier way to
play is} 5... exf3 {, but White is very active after} 6. Nxf3 d5 7. Bd3 g6 8.
