{A lot of people are put off by the Dutch because of the number of sidelines
that White can choose from. Two of White's main options are 2 Nc3 and 2 Bg5.
--- I am lucky because I always start the game 1 d4 e6, as I am happy to enter
into a French Defence after 2 e4 has been played. Buy my book 'Attacking Chess:
The French: A Dynamic Repertoire for Black' (published by Everyman Chess) if
you want to learn this exciting opening! --- Occasionally, I do start with 1...f5, but you must know what to play against 2 Nc3 or 2 Bg5, as these moves are
quite popular and can be rather tricky. --- Let me introduce you to both of
these moves.} 1. d4 f5 2. Nc3 {White is aiming to play a quick e4 with this
move. It is worth stopping this plan.} (2. Bg5 {is an interesting move and one
that Kasparov has tried. White plays the opening like the Trompowsky Attack,
with the intention of making it difficult for Black to develop. We will take a
look at this move later on. --- BRAINSTORMING POINT! --- As a general rule of
thumb, I would suggest that Black sticks to the solid} Nf6 {. Despite the fact
that his pawn structure will be damaged, he will have good compensation in the
form of the bishop pair as well as an excellent grip on the position.} ({If
you are in a gambling mood then you might want to consider the line given
below starting with} 2... h6 3. Bh4 g5 4. e4 Rh7 $5 {. --- To be honest, I
have serious doubts about this variation and I would not be surprised to learn
that White has a refutation to ...Rh7. I first covered this line in another
Everyman book entitled Dutch: Dangerous Weapon. A lot of the original ideas of
this line are included in this publication.})) (2. Nh3 $5 {is also an
interesting idea. White's knight is often well placed on f4, so this is
actually a sensible plan. The positions that arise from this variation
normally involve a lot of piece manoeuvring. However, I doubt whether this
idea can seriously worry Black.}) 2... d5 {This move is now playable as White
will struggle to play c4, due to the fact that his knight is in the way.
Incidentally, c4 is the main way for White to damage Black's pawn structure.
Black should be aiming to play ...a6 and ...c5 in most variations.} ({Another
solid choice is} 2... Nf6 3. Bg5 d5 4. Bxf6 exf6 {with a roughly equal game.})
*

