{2...h6 3 Bh4 g5 4 e4 Rh7!?!? is a very risky move but as it is so interesting
and complicated, I thought that it needed to be included in this chapter. If
you want to play without any risk then you should play 2 Bg5 Nf6 3 Bxf6 exf6
followed by ...d5 and Black has a solid position. --- In order to get to grips
with this position, I would suggest that you take a look at some of the top
Grandmaster games in this line. As this line is not so theoretical, the player
who has a greater understanding of the middlegame will often be triumphant.} 1.
d4 f5 2. Bg5 h6 ({The major alternative that we need to consider is} 2... Nf6 {
. --- The 'solid' approach. Black allows White to double his pawns in the hope
that his two bishops will spring to life later on. With careful play, this
line should offer Black an equal game. I won't delve too deeply into the
variations, as I have already mentioned that this type of position is very
solid. Let's take a look at two examples of this.} 3. -- (3. Bxf6 {is the most
natural move.} exf6 4. e3 g6 {(this is a solid way to give extra protection to
Black's pawn chain)} 5. h4 d5 {(Black relies on this move in order to take
firm control of the centre)} 6. c4 Be6 7. cxd5 Bxd5 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. Nge2 Bf7 10.
g3 Bd6 11. Bg2 O-O 12. a3 Ne7 13. Nf4 c6 14. Nd3 a5 15. Qc2 Qb6 16. O-O Bb3 {
. Black has a very pleasant position with no weaknesses. Furthermore, he also
has the option to play ...c5. We have been following the game A.Grischuk-A.Moiseenko, Russian Team Championship 2005.}) (3. e3 {. This kind of approach
can hardly be dangerous. I.Sokolov-S.Agdestein, Oslo 1996, continued} e6 4.
Bd3 Be7 5. Ne2 O-O 6. O-O Nd5 $5 7. Bxe7 Qxe7 8. a3 Nf6 {and Black has a very
comfortable position. He can either aim to take control of e4 by playing ...b6
and ...Bb7, or he can consider the standard plan of ...d6 followed by ...e5.} (
8... --))) 3. Bh4 ({Or:} 3. Bc1 $5 {Another Stephen Gordon idea! In this
position,} d5 {looks like a sensible way to continue. Black will aim to play ...c5 after he has developed on the kingside.}) (3. Bf4 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e4 $5 {
The positions that arise from this typical gambit tend to lead to a messy but
equal game. Just what you want when playing the Dutch!} fxe4 6. f3 Bb4 {(Black
should aim to always have control over e4)} 7. fxe4 O-O 8. Qd3 d5 9. exd5 exd5
10. O-O-O {with an equal game.}) 3... g5 4. e4 ({White can also play safe with
the less aggressive} 4. e3 {. --- Black should be comfortable as long as he
plays against White's dark-squared bishop. For example,} Bg7 5. Bg3 (5. Qh5+ {
does not help White's position; for example, after} Kf8 {, White's queen can
actually become a target:} 6. Bg3 Nf6 7. Qf3 d6 8. Bd3 Nc6 9. Nc3 (9. Bxf5 g4
10. Qf4 e5) 9... e5 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. O-O-O Qe7) 5... d6 $1 {. ---
BRAINSTORMING POINT! --- It is important for Black to play ...e5! as this move
will help to suffocate the white bishop on g3.} 6. h4 g4 7. Ne2 e5 {and after
this pawn break, the position is now equal.}) 4... Rh7 $5 5. Qh5+ ({White can
also try:} 5. Be2 Kf7 $5 {(crazy but fine!)} 6. Bg3 f4 7. Bxf4 gxf4 8. e5 {.
White has a slight initiative but if Black manages to defend this position, he
will be better.}) (5. Bc4 {looks logical but it does run into} d5 $1 {(this
move wins a piece but the position is still very complicated)} 6. Qh5+ Rf7 7.
exd5 (7. Bxd5 e6) 7... Nf6 8. Qg6 Qd6 9. Nf3 Ne4 {and Black is clearly better.}
) 5... Rf7 6. Nf3 Nf6 7. Qg6 Nc6 {This is the critical position, where White
has a number of dangerous options:} 8. -- (8. Bc4 {This is certainly dangerous.
} e6 9. Bxg5 $1 (9. Ne5 Nxe5 10. dxe5 Nxe4 {is good for Black}) 9... hxg5 10.
Nxg5 Qe7 11. exf5 Nxd4 $1 12. fxe6 Nxe6 13. Bxe6 dxe6 14. Nc3 Nd5 15. Nce4 e5
$1 16. O-O-O Bf5 17. Qxf7+ Qxf7 18. Nxf7 Kxf7 19. Ng5+ Kf6 20. Rxd5 Kxg5 {With
an unclear position, but there may well have been improvements along the way
for both sides.}) (8. e5 Ne4 $5 9. d5 Nb4 10. e6 {This position is completely
bonkers!} Nxc2+ 11. Kd1 dxe6 12. Kxc2 Qxd5 {Who knows what is going on?!}) (8.
exf5 gxh4 9. Bc4 d5 10. Bb5 $1 Nd7 11. Nc3 Bg7 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Qxc6 Rb8 14.
Nxd5 Kf8 15. Nxc7 Kg8 16. Ne6 Qa5+ 17. c3 Qxf5 {Yet again, the position has
become very complicated!}) (8. Bxg5 $6 {. We've already seen how Black
