after} 4. e3 Nf6 5. Bd3 e6 6. Nf3 Be7 7. Ne2 $1 {and White prepares to play c4
with a small advantage}) 4. e3 (4. e4 $5 {is interesting, for example,} dxe4 5.
f3 Nf6 6. fxe4 fxe4 7. Bc4 Nc6 8. Nge2 {. --- BRAINSTORMING POINT! --- White's
light-squared bishop is a very strong piece. How can Black swap it off?} Na5 $1
9. Bb3 Nxb3 10. axb3 Bf5 11. Qd2 e6 12. O-O-O Bb4 {and I prefer Black's
position}) 4... Nf6 5. a3 e6 6. Nf3 Bd7 7. Be2 c5 $1 {(this is the reason why
