Ne2 {BRAINSTORMING POINT! --- White is planning to play c4. How should Black
stop this plan?} c4 $1 {is simple and good. Black gains space on the queenside
giving him a small edge.}) (3. Nf3 {This move is nothing to write home about
but it is worth having a quick look at what happens if White plays slowly and
fianchettoes his light-squared bishop:} Nf6 4. g3 $6 {(a dubious-looking move
that does not seem to fit into White's opening system)} e6 5. Bg2 {. ---
BRAINSTORMING POINT! --- Black can obviously play a normal Stonewall set-up,
but in this position he can attack the centre straightaway as White's pawn is
on c2 and not c4. How should Black do this?} c5 $1 {This looks like the best
option! With this move, Black will take the initiative after} 6. O-O cxd4 7.
Nb5 Bd7 8. Nbxd4 Nc6 {.}) (3. e4 $6 {does not seem to work well here, for
example,} dxe4 $1 4. f3 {. --- BRAINSTORMING POINT! --- Black could play ...Nf6 transposing back to a position that we looked at earlier but there is a
better move! How can Black start a counterattack in the centre?} e5 $1 {This
looks like the best move. Black strikes out!} 5. dxe5 Qxd1+ 6. Nxd1 (6. Kxd1
Nc6 7. Nd5 Kd8 8. Bg5+ Nge7 9. f4 h6 10. Nxe7 Nxe7 11. Bxe7+ Kxe7 {works out
