{To play ...e6 or ...e5? --- The main position that we are going to look at in
this chapter arises after the following starting moves:} 1. c4 f5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3.
g3 e6 4. Bg2 Be7 5. d3 O-O {. It is worth noting that this position can be
reached via several different move orders. --- This is a fairly popular
approach among club players. The English Opening is an easy system to learn,
where White will often play the first eight moves or so without much thought.
--- I have always found that the Dutch works rather well against the English
set-up and my own results on the black side of this opening have been very
good. The position resembles that of a reversed Grand Prix Attack, where Black
aims to attack on the kingside whilst White focuses his attention on the
queenside. --- BRAINSTORMING POINT! --- The first thing to bear in mind when
playing against the English set-up is whether or not you can achieve the ...e5
advance in one move, i.e. not waste time by playing ...e6 followed by ...e5 at
a later stage. I am not going to dwell on this too much, but ideally Black
would like to play ...e5 as early as possible. --- In general, I will play ...e5 if I believe that my opponent won't respond with a quick d4 which is, to my
mind, the best response to ...e5. This will often be the case when playing
against the average 1 c4 player as they are usually happy to just play with
the same set-up.} *

