{Let's now take a look at what both sides are trying to achieve in the
following position:} 1. -- (1. -- {White's Strategy: After 5 d3, White is no
longer trying to stop Black from playing the typical ...e5 advance. Instead,
White will aim to play around this move. This is normally achieved in two
different ways: 1) White plays e4. Club players will often play this move
without too much thought. The main reason for this is due to an excellent book
that GM Tony Kosten wrote on the English. In this book, Tony recommended a
set-up based on e4 known as the Botvinnik System. --- I have a specific line
that I enjoy playing against this set-up. This is one of the main reasons why
I avoid playing ...d6 too early. My plan is to develop my dark-squared bishop
to either b4 or c5, a plan that is not possible with a pawn on d6. --- 2)
White decides to concentrate his play on the queenside by playing moves like
Rb1, b4, b5 etc. This can lead to an interesting battle where Black attacks on
the kingside and White attacks on the queenside. --- Personally, I believe
that White's best set-up is one based on e3 and Nge2. These two moves prevent
Black from attacking on the kingside. Black will often rely on the move ...f4
to start an attack and by playing e3 and Nge2, White takes control of this
critical square.}) (1. -- {Black's Strategy: Black's strategy can be
summarised in a few points and is playable against both of White's set-ups
mentioned above. --- 1) Play ...e5. This critical move shows its face again!
You can sometimes wait before playing this advance in order to keep some
flexibility with regard to the placement of the dark-squared bishop. This is
especially true when White adopts plan '1' mentioned above, but eventually you
should always aim to advance with ...e5. --- 2) Develop the knight to c6.
Black no longer has to worry about White playing d5 so ...Nc6 makes a lot more
sense. Black can often meet the b4-b5 advance with ...Qe8 and ...Nd8. In a
number of my games, I have managed to follow up with ...g5, ...g4, ...Nf7 and ...Ng5 and my pieces are all positioned around White's king! --- 3) Play the
typical manoeuvre ...Qe8 and ...Qh5 in order to place more pressure on White's
kingside. --- 4) Advance on the kingside with ...g5 and ...g4. --- Black can
always consider playing ...c6 as well, but this move does have its advantages
and disadvantages. On the plus side, Black can then play ...Qe8 ...Bd8 and
either ...Bb6 or ...Bc7, when the dark-squared bishop finds a new lease of
life.}) *

