{IM Robert Bellin is a 'Jedi Master' of the Dutch, there is no doubt about it!
One of Bellin's first books, entitled, 'Winning with the Dutch' actually
inspired me to play the Classical Dutch. Robert has played the Dutch for most
of his life so it is well worth taking a look at his games in this opening.
--- This next game is very interesting. Robert followed GM Magnus Carlsen's
idea by playing an early d3. However my response, which is rather rare, looks
perfectly satisfactory and also leads to some very exciting positions.} 1. Nf3
f5 2. d3 $5 {This is an interesting idea that has been used by Carlsen. White
aims to disrupt Black's position by playing an early e4. Luckily, I have an
idea against this plan.} d6 {Black aims to meet e4 with ...e5. I have
previously written about this in my first book, 'Play the Classical Dutch'.} 3.
e4 e5 4. Nc3 c5 $5 {An interesting idea. Black establishes a strong centre and
most importantly, I take control of the d4-square. Nonetheless, there are
downsides to this plan such as my lack of development and my weaknesses on the
light squares, especially f5 and d5.} 5. g3 Be7 $5 {Played in order to stop
Nh4, a move that would immediately put pressure on my f5-pawn.} ({In the
theory section, we will concentrate on the very interesting} 5... Nc6 $5 {.})
6. Bh3 $1 {A good move as White targets the light squares. Any other move
would have left me with a comfortable game.} g6 7. exf5 {I had seen this move
coming and I was worried about 7...gxf5 8 Nh4! which looks very dangerous for
Black. Instead, I had another idea in mind...} h5 $5 {This stops White from
playing Qh5+ at a later stage. As some of you may be aware, I am rather fond
of pushing my h-pawn and I rarely get a chance to do this in the Dutch. After
just seven moves, we have reached a bizarre position.} 8. Bg2 $2 {This is a
bad move.} ({White has a couple of good options:} 8. Nd5 $1 {when he can claim
an advantage.}) (8. Nh4 $1 {will be looked at in the next game. --- In the
Theory section, we will investigate whether Black had an improvement earlier
on.}) 8... gxf5 9. Bd2 $2 {This is too passive. Black has a space advantage
but has fallen behind in development.} ({White should have played} 9. h4 {as
this move takes control of the g5-square.}) 9... Nc6 10. Qe2 Be6 11. h4 Nf6 12.
Ng5 Bg8 {Black keeps control of the d5-square.} 13. f4 {At this moment, I was
feeling very happy with my position. White's king looks to be in some danger
and my knights are about to move onto some great squares.} Nd4 14. Qd1 Ng4 $1
15. Nd5 {A peculiar position. Just take a look at the knights! I will soon
exchange my bishops for White's knights which are clearly stronger. I also had
a cunning idea in mind...} e4 $1 {This move opens the lines towards White's
king.} 16. dxe4 Bxg5 17. hxg5 Bxd5 18. exd5 {A critical position. 18...Qe7+
looks like the obvious choice but is there a better move?} Qb6 $1 {I have to
make it difficult for White to castle and this move does just that. I expect
that I am now winning.} 19. c3 ({In response to} 19. O-O {, I would have played
} c4 {as I had seen the following attractive line:} 20. Re1+ Ne2+ {leading to
a winning position for Black.}) 19... O-O-O $1 20. cxd4 {The attack plays
itself.} Rde8+ 21. Kf1 Qb5+ 22. Kg1 {I was originally planning to play 22...Qd3 in this position but I could not find a win after 23 Be1. Subsequently, I
found an easier option.} Qxb2 $1 {Threatening ...Qxd4 and ...Qf2#. White has
only one way to stop this.} 23. Be1 Re2 24. Bf3 {A unique winning move now
appeared...} Rh2 $1 {. I am now threatening ...Rxh1, ...Qh2+ and then ...Ne3#.
White cannot stop all of the threats, so Robert resigned. I was obviously very
happy with this game as it felt good to checkmate an expert in the Dutch in
under twenty-five moves!} 0-1

