position, which eventually ended 0-1, M.Krasenkow-V.Moskalenko, Hoogeveen 2013.
}) 4. g3 {This set-up with d3-d4 and g3 looks rather dubious to me. It seems
that the wasted tempo White gave away does little to help his position.} ({The
other option is} 4. c4 {(trying to force d5 looks a lot more logical)} Nf6 5.
d5 Bb4+ $1 6. Bd2 Bxd2+ 7. Qxd2 Ne4 8. Qd1 Ne7 9. dxe6 d5 $5 {, is now
interesting but probably good for White after} (9... d6 10. Nbd2 Bxe6 {and
Black can be very happy with the way that the opening has gone}) 10. cxd5 Bxe6
11. dxe6 Qxd1+ 12. Kxd1 Nxf2+ 13. Ke1 Nxh1 {, when Black's knight will be lost
on h1.}) 4... Nf6 5. Bg2 d6 {Black plans ...e5 quickly, giving him a nice
position.} (5... Be7 6. c4 $1 {is similar to below.}) 6. O-O $6 (6. c4 $1 {was
a much better idea, aiming to play d5. This is stronger than in some previous
variations as Black can no longer play ...Bb4 +.} e5 7. d5 Nb8 {looks unclear.
If White can quickly take advantage of the e6-square then he may be able to
generate a good initiative.}) 6... Be7 7. c4 e5 8. d5 Nb8 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Ng5
Na6 11. Rb1 h6 12. Ne6 Bxe6 13. dxe6 c6 14. b4 Qc8 {. Black was doing well in
N.Grandelius-E.Berg, Borlange 2014.} *

