1. Nf3 f5 2. d3 Nc6 3. e4 e5 {The point behind ...Nc6! White now has a couple
of options, with 4 Nc3 being the most popular:} 4. -- (4. d4 {We have now
reached the Vienna Game, via a very strange move order. This position more
often occurs, with colours reversed (but tempi exactly the same!), after the
sequence of moves: 1 e4 e5 2 Nc3 Nf6 3 f4 d5. --- I suggest that you take a
look at that opening to know what to play here; it is really outside the scope
of this book!}) (4. exf5 {This should be met by:} d5 $1 (4... Nf6 {is also
interesting but gives White the option of playing} 5. h3 {, when the position
is very closely linked to a reverse Kings Gambit after} d5 6. g4 {. Now my
suggested way to play for Black would be} g6 7. g5 Nh5 8. f6 Bd6 {which is
very similar in spirit to 1 e4 e5 2 f2 exf4 3 Nf3 g4 4 Nc3 d6 5 d4 Bg7 6 g3 g4
7 Nh4 f3. --- The text 4...d5! simply gains control of the centre of the board,
whilst threatening to win the pawn back on f5 with ...Bxf5. Let's take a look
at what could happen if White tries to hold onto the extra pawn}) 5. g4 h5 $1 {
A typical way to break up White's kingside pawns. Black already has the
initiative.} 6. gxh5 Bxf5 7. Bg5 Be7 8. Nh4 $2 Bh7 $2 ({missing} 8... Bb4+ 9.
c3 Qxg5 10. Nxf5 Qxf5 11. cxb4 Nf6 {when Black would be winning}) 9. Bxe7 Qxe7
10. Ng6 Bxg6 11. hxg6 Nf6 12. Nd2 O-O-O 13. c3 Kb8 14. Qc2 Ng4 15. Be2 Nxf2 $1
{A beautiful way to open up White's king. Black's attack is devastating. The
game J.Laurent-A.Gorovets, Lille 2013, continued:} 16. Kxf2 Qh4+ 17. Kg1 Rdf8
18. Bf3 e4 $1 {Opening up more lines towards White's bare king on g1.} 19. dxe4
dxe4 20. Nxe4 Rxf3 21. Rf1 Ne5 22. Qe2 Rhf8 23. Rxf3 Nxf3+ 24. Kg2 Qg4+ 25. Ng3
Nh4+ 26. Kg1 Qh3 {0-1. A very pretty game!}) (4. Nc3 {This is the position
that you are most likely to reach after playing 2...Nc6.} Nf6 5. exf5 d5 {We
now see the main reason why Black avoided playing ...d6. Black can now play ...d5 in one move, saving a tempo.} 6. d4 exd4 {The best move.} (6... e4 $6 {
looks obvious but is a mistake after} 7. Nh4 {, when Black's compensation is
somewhat lacking}) 7. Nxd4 Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Bxf5 {A critical position for the
evaluation of this opening. On all current evidence and computer calculation,
Black can look to the future with confidence. --- BRAINSTORMING POINT! --- It
is worth remembering that in a number of lines the black king is best placed
on f7 after a check on the e-file.} 9. Bg5 {This looks like the best place to
develop the bishop, as on g5 White creates some pressure against Black's
d-pawn.} ({White has also tried} 9. Bb5+ $6 {aiming for quick development, but
this falls short:} c6 10. O-O Bxc2 {(brave but correct)} 11. Bg5 Be7 12. Bxf6
Bxf6 13. Rae1+ Kf7 14. Qd2 Bg6 {. Black had a big advantage and went on to win
in P.Batchelor-N.Pert, British Championship 2014}) 9... Bxc2 {It is best to be
brave; other options allow White to castle queenside.} 10. Rc1 Bg6 11. h4 {A
new move from the 'Hawk' but it does not change the evaluation of the position.
} ({White has also tried:} 11. Qe5+ $6 Kf7 {was better for Black in J.Gdanski-M.Bartel, Polish Championship 2010}) (11. Bxf6 {is also better for
Black:} Qxf6 12. Qe3+ Qe7 13. Qxe7+ Kxe7 14. Nxd5+ Kd7) (11. Bd3 {looks
logical, but Black still holds an edge after} c6 12. Bxg6+ hxg6 13. O-O Bd6 {
. Quite often the black king sits happily on f7 in this variation, and this is
the case here after} 14. Rfe1+ Kf7 $1) 11... h6 12. Qe5+ Kf7 {The safest
square for the black king!} 13. h5 Bh7 14. Nxd5 {The position looks very scary
for Black, but with a bit of care it is White who must be on his guard.} c6 $6
{This is OK,} ({but there was a better option in} 14... Bd6 $1 15. Bc4 (15.
Bxf6 Bxe5 16. Bxd8 Raxd8 17. Bc4 Bxb2 18. Nxc7+ Ke7 19. Rd1 Rxd1+ 20. Kxd1 Kd6
{and Black is clearly better}) 15... Bxe5 16. Nxf6+ Ke7 $1 17. Nd5+ Kd7 18.
Bxd8 Raxd8 {. Black's two bishops give him the advantage}) 15. Nc3 Bd6 {And
after many adventures the game ended a draw in J.Hawkins-N.Pert, British
Championship 2014.}) *

