1. Nf3 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 d6 $5 {I wanted to play ...e5 in one move. Nowadays,
this is the move order that I favour.} 4. O-O e5 5. d3 {So far, I was very
happy with the outcome of the opening as I had managed to play ...e5 in one
move.} Be7 6. Nc3 $5 {My opponent makes his intentions clear. He is aiming to
play e4 which leads to a unique position. This plan has never really worried
me as Black can respond in one of two ways: 1) Simply capture on e4 and
develop sensibly. --- 2) Aim to meet e4 with ...f4!? --- The second plan is
the most interesting option so I immediately put this plan into motion.} O-O 7.
e4 Nc6 8. h3 Qe8 9. Re1 f4 $5 {This pawn sacrifice leads to good play for
Black. By capturing on f4, White also weakens his kingside.} 10. gxf4 exf4 11.
Bxf4 Nh5 12. Bg3 Ne5 {Black has good play for the pawn as all of his pieces
head towards White's king. This is just the type of position that Black should
be happy playing!} 13. Nd5 Bd8 14. d4 Nxf3+ 15. Bxf3 Nxg3 16. fxg3 Bxh3 17. Bg2
Qg6 {. Black is slightly better due to White's weakened kingside but the game
actually ended in a draw. --- The main thing to consider is how you should
respond if White plays e4 without c4? --- If you can play ...f4 in this
opening, then brilliant. If not, then the simple exchange on e4 should be
enough for an equal game.} *

