{Where do you go from here?} 1. -- (1. -- {Providing that you have studied
most of the material in this book, you are now ready to start playing the
Classical Dutch! --- Welcome to its mad world. The opening needs more
followers and like me, I hope that you have taken a shine to it. --- In the
past, when learning a new opening, I have often had trouble getting to grips
with the middlegame plans. From experience, I have found that a good way to
improve after studying an opening book/DVD is to look at the games of the
experts in that variation. You will often pick up tips and ideas along the way.
--- For this reason, I have included a list of players who are considered to
be "Jedi Masters" of the Classical Dutch. You can search for the games of
these players in any chess database. --- Throughout this book, you may have
noticed that I have used a large number of my own games. This is not because I
consider myself to be the greatest Dutch Jedi around but instead for the
reason that I understand my own thought processes better than anyone. --- In
my progression as a Classical Dutch player, I have often had to stand on my
own two feet or use trial and error to discover the best variations out there.
This has really helped me think in an original way, but it has also been quite
hard work! Luckily, I have already "tested the water" so you can now progress
without too much trouble. --- Anyway, let's move on to some other chess
players who are known to be avid followers of the Dutch, especially the
Classical Dutch. It is worth noting that I have chosen more modern players. If
you are interested, you can always look at the history section of this book
for a list of 'chess legends' that have tried their hand at the Dutch.}) (1. --
{Igor Naumkin: During my research, this gentleman's name kept cropping up. A
number of his games have greatly contributed to the progression of the Dutch.
--- Robert Bellin: Robert wrote one of the first books that ever dealt with
the Classical Dutch. This man has been a mover and shaker with this opening
for years. --- Thomas Rendle: A young English International Master who is an
expert in the Leningrad Dutch. Thomas has found great ways to play against
'Anti-Dutch' lines and I have learnt quite a lot from him by following his
encounters in the Dutch. --- Nigel Short: Nigel used the Dutch regularly in
his younger years. Will he return? --- Anatoly Vaisser: Anatoly has had some
great victories using the Dutch Defence. --- Vladimir Malaniuk: A very strong
Grandmaster whose games have featured in this book. --- Igor Glek: Another
ex-2600+ Grandmaster who used to score very well with the opening. ---
Alexandre Dgebuadze: Some of Alexandre's games have also featured in this book.
Alexandre seems to have a very good understanding of when he should play ...e5!
}) (1. -- {The above mentioned list should suffice for now. One of the most
interesting things to look at is the different ways in which these players
